76561198079167443,Not Recommended,276810,20257195,"Posted: 3 January, 2016",all,bryanjkautzman,"This game has a lot going for it.  It's a great turn-based strategy game with individual levelling for all characters.  There is a great feeling of satisfaction that goes into levelling up a party.  To that extent, it's a lot of fun, but it has some pretty serious issues.This is a ""hardcore"" style game.  If a character gets hurt, he stays hurt.  If a character dies, he's gone forever.  this is an interesting dynamic which I typically do not like, but it's okay if it's done well.  In this game, it is done well.  Most of the time.  however, towards the end game, it turns into a game breaker, and I'll explain why.The story missions are challenging, to say the least.  No, I'll go one step beyond that.  They are hard.First of all, they put my warband into a tactically stupid situation that I would never put myself into.  Both of my archers were paired with my mage, and two of them were dead before they even had a turn on my first play-through.  On my second playthrough, after losing one of my archers to perma-death and firing the other because he was pretty much worthless after suffering a brain injury, I used only melee characters with much better success.  That doesn't change the fact that my warband was pretty much decimated due to a flaw in the game.  Oh well.  Another 20-30 hours of play time to get my warband powerful enough to take on the mission again.On my second playthrough, I was plugging along just fine.  The basic premise behind that mission is that there is an invicincible opponent that goes around destroying all of your characters without batting an eye while the player struggles to figure out how to inflict damage on her.  When I finally figured out that you need to disable the pillars, it took three turns to arrive at the first pillar while this enemy is mercilessly killing my warband.  When I finally arrive, I think ""finally.  I might be able to inflict some damage!""  But no.  I need some shard or something, and who knows where the heck that is.  Suddenly, it sinks in.  Even with the shard, it will take 5-6 turns to disable all of the pillars.  And that's not including the amount of time it will take to find the shard.  So, yeah.  My warband was completely decimated a second time, and I'm not willing to put 20-30 hours of play time into this game again just to get my warband powerful enough to take on the mission again.Simply put, when I purchased this game, I was looking for two things.  I wanted a turn-based strategy game.  Check.  Secondly, I wanted a game where I had the ability to level up individual characters in my war party.  Check.  What I did not want is a puzzle game where if you get it wrong the first time, you realize you've wasted 20-30 hours of your life.  If I wanted to solve puzzles, I'd go play Portal.  There is a reason why I don't play Portal.  It's because I hate puzzle games.  What's worse than a puzzle game?  A puzzle game where failure is pretty much permanent.If that type of frustration is what you are looking for in a game, then by all means:  Purchase Mordheim.  As it sits, this game took over 100 hours of my time, and I want that time back."
,Recommended,276810,34401271,Posted: 21 August,all,Bobby Boy Freed,"This game has scratched an itch that I didn't even know that I had...I bought this on sale on a whim (i.e. had enough Steam credit that it didn't hurt to buy) despite actually having marked it as ""Not Interested"" in one of my discovery queues. But as I have been waiting for X-COM 2: War of the Chosen to come out, this one popped up as a recommendation. I decided to give it a chance and I have been blown away!It's not overly polished, and frankly it's very repetitive in gameplay (deploy your warriors and scoop up as much loot as possible before the inevitable battle begins and hope to God that the RNG is favorable, praying that no one in your team gets permanently injured or at worse dead). However, I am finding myself nearing 70 hours of gameplay and I still don't feel I have scratched the surface of all the game seems to offer. I am currently on my fourth warband, haven't even tried any of the ""campaign"" missions, haven't even touched any of the other warband types other than the mercenaries, and I still can't wait to get back to it for just one more journey into the City of the Damned to try my luck and skill just one more time hoping to get to the next warband level, getting more experience for that lower level grunt, and hoping to find that one superior looted item that will make you a little more stronger the next time you go in for more of the same.It's a numbers game as much as a skill game and I am loving it! My first two warbands went horribly wrong and my third one actually started to get reasonably strong before I decided it was time to scrap it too after all of the lessons I had learned on what not to do in my first failed attempts. And that's when the game really starts to come into its own. Unfortunately the game can be very, very unforgiving to a newbie such as myself and that's what keeps a lot from going on further with it. I can understand why so many are turned off by it but also see why there are those dedicated players who have also literally put a thousand hours and more into this one. The ecstasy of a well fought victory as well as the utter dismay at a battle gone wrong are an addicting contrast, though I have finally really been learning to have more victories than defeats (around 90% won with my current warband) with the occasional disappointing fallout for an injured warrior even under victory conditions.This game is definitely not for everyone. I can understand that. But if you are looking for a game that really makes you think out strategy as you position your warrior pieces and the tacticts to get them there, this is a game for you. Even a small skirmish can take extra time now that I have learned more about the game mechanics and the opponent AI. If you know where to look and are patient, you can make good judgments about where the enemy will be. You can know pretty much what you are up against and position your warriors accordingly. Also, learning tips such as stay together, don't always ambush, and don't be afraid to disengage or even flee from battle at times, can make a big difference after failing to do some of these things the first time(s) through.Also, mitigating damage, is something you need to be prepared to do. There are some great skills and some awesome buffs, but be aware that almost everything has its negative effects as well. Do you take the potion or leave it at camp? Do you apply this enhancement or save it for later knowing that weapon or armor might be the next to be lost? Do you spend the gold for that skill that could be lost forever when you get unlucky with that warrior the next time you send them out. It's loss manager's dream! The first time you cast a spell and have your warrior permanently knocked out for the rest of the battle is one of the worst feelings you can have. However, when you see the enemy attempt to do the same thing but not only stuns himself, but also your three warriors that are currently pummeling on him, you just have to smile (the enemy still ended up being toast that very same round). It really is a masochist's dream, but I am now convinced you can get better at this game despite the random nature of so many of its events. I haven't even come close to experiencing all I can with this warband, and I am already envisioning which one I want to start with for the next playthrough AFTER I finish at least the first and maybe second campaign mission with this one.To be honest, recommending a game like this which has almost absolutely no story and absolutely no purpose other than building up the most versatile and ferocious warband you can actually seems ludicrous to me, but I still can't recommend it enough. If you don't want to pay full price to try it, I understand, but you might actually like it. I liked it so much that despite buying the base game on sale, I missed the sale for the DLC, but bought it at full price anyway (a reason for many of the negative reviews you might be reading) because I have truly enjoyed it that much and didn't want to have to wait for the DLC to come back down in price again before trying it.You have been warned. This game is definitely not for everyone. Some will wish it had never been programmed. But some of you on the edge just need to give it a try and you might very well find yourself as sucked into it as I have been. Just one more mission into the City of the Damned!!"
,Recommended,276810,19142288,"Posted: 18 November, 2015",all,wozron,"PRE-RELEASE REVIEWI have been playing Mordheim: City of the Damned (M:CotD) for about eight weeks.The Early Access copy was not supplied by anything other than my own cash.THE UPS:-A multi-dimensional challenge with many different builds, challenges, and tactics.-A really nice aesthetic representation of Mordheim post-comet.-Rewards intelligence, tactics, foresight, planning and force multiplication while retaining a random factor.-No two games ever work out the same.-A devoted community already developing.THE MEHS-The RNG *WILL* bend you over at some point. Not because it's unfair, but more because you're planning opposed rolls based on YOUR probabilities.A fictitious example: Your captain attacks and the system tells you that you have a 90% to-hit. What it doesn't tell you is that with enemy abilities, skills etc., you actually only have a 30% chance to hit.If you knew it was 30% overall, you might choose to disengage and/or switch to ranged. But you won't be given this opportunity.-Min/max builds and system gaming already rife. Needs a balancing mechanic.THE BAD-I haven't won the lottery so it's going to be a while before I can retire and play 24/7.RECOMMENDED AUDIENCE-Necromunda fans-Mordheim fans-WHFB fans pre-WHFB sharkjumping olympics-Born during the Vietnam War-Super cool people who used to play tabletop games but developed careers-Stoners-Obsessive-compulsives-People who are super talented at painting minis and building terrain, plus they brew their own beer, but not any more-Sad old tabletop wargamers looking to relive their glory days-Awesome cool people who just don't give a tinker's curse about K/D ratios, lanespam, grenade spam etc. and just want a thinker's game linked by an ongoing campaign-Me and every gamer I respectSeriously 10/10 top effort. This game deserves to succeed, if only to open up DLC, Necromunda, WW2: the Turnbased Third-person Tactical game, et cetera. If you're a thinking gamer not a twitch gamer, don't think: buy."
76561198006482579,Not Recommended,276810,24735389,"Posted: 5 August, 2016",all,z',"There's a lot to like about Mordheim, but not enough to recommend it. The visuals are solid: graphics are good, aesthetic customization is satisfyingly deep, and the ruined city, forgive the expression, comes alive. Though some have criticized the gameplay, I really liked the combat system, and had a lot of fun in the actual fights.However:The campaign becomes extremely unfun pretty quickly because of how the game compensatses for the poor fighting skills of the AI, namely, massive, massive bonuses. You can see it in the description of the difficulty of a given mission, but what isn't clear is how the game ""balances"" the strength of your warband as you level up. Enemy warbands will have a rating similar to yours, but will have /all/ their members leveled. In addition to this, they'll have a composition similar to yours, so if you have six members, they have six members. If you have one of your special heroes, they'll have one of their special heroes. One of the biggest frustrations I experienced was leveling up my Cult warband until I could, FINALLY, hire the Possessed. Once I fielded him, though, I found myself up against a fully leveled and upgraded Augur that handed his♥♥♥♥♥to him. Read some guides, found out that people that Possessed heroes were underpowered, so I ditched him, and started leveling up for the Spawn. Got the Spawn, and then faced a fully leveled and upgraded Rat Ogre. That was when I stopped playing.Maybe I'd like it better in multiplayer, but the campaign became just incredinly unfun to play after a while. The only way to win those kinds of match is to get lucky in the set up, and then exploit the very poor AI strategy. Which, by the way, is to just run straight at you along whatever road is closest. I have never seen the AI go after objectives, which also makes it hard, bordering on impossible, for you to do the same. Unless you get REALLY lucky, expect most skirmishes to devolve into a scrum, which is why the best and only strategy is to keep your whole warband together at all times.But it on sale, maybe, but I'd give it a pass. It's more frustrating than fun."
