76561198027331282,Not Recommended,276810,31072305,Posted: 10 April,all,Your Favorite Dwarf,"I want to like this game--I really do--but it doesn't feel .  The amount of playtime on my account is a little deceptive (as the vast majority of my experience with the game comes from watching others play and backseat gaming with them), but my criticisms are largely echoed in some of the other negative reviews here, so I don't feel as though my observations are incorrect.The first of my gripes with the game is the lack of focus.  I never played the tabletop version of Mordeheim, but I heard it mentioned that there are two different ""phases"" of the game that have been combined for the purposes of this game.  To be honest, that doesn't surprise me.  If you don't collect all of the loot on the map, you get practically nothing except to walk home with a beat-to-hell warband.  This is the first game I've ever played where I've felt punished by kicking butt and taking names, which is incredibly confusing.  What's the point of making combat so hardcore and brutal that warbands have to focus on decimating their opponents in order not to get demolished in turn, only to punish them for doing so and not exploring the map?  It makes no sense.The second is the♥♥♥♥♥♥poor RNG system.  Tell me that it's just the nature of dice-rolling all you'd like, I have a hard time believing that missing 5-6 times in a row with an 89% chance to hit (and doing so consistently; almost every game I've been a part of goes the same way) is just bad luck.  It feels like the game is actively working against you, especially when the opponent nonchalantly murders all of your minions because, no matter how tactically you plan out your approach, your troops couldn't hit the broad side of a barn.  I've played enough XCOM to not feel disheartened by my opponents' weapons doing substantially more than mine in the beginning of the game (it would be incredibly boring if you didn't have to work for those early victories), but being wholly unable to hit your opponent with your wet noodle of a sword and getting cut down because of it just makes the game feel tedious.The game looks beautiful, and Warhammer is one of my favorite fantasy universes ever, so I came into this heavily biased towards liking it.  It just doesn't feel fair.  ""Fair"" isn't a euphamism for ""coddled"", here; the game just feels unbalanced to the point of being a wholly miserable experience despite the flashes of brilliance it occasionally displays.  I want to like it, I really do, but my experience here has just kind of left a bad taste in my mouth."
