76561198009291175,Recommended,276810,20475220,"Posted: 11 January, 2016",all,Frogspawned,"I love this game, but at time of writing this review I have to say that it is very deeply flawed.For the most part a faithful and enjoyable adaption of Games Workshop's specialist squad-based combat system, City of the Damned is a wonderfully dark, gritty, tense and tactical experience...... once you actually load the damn thing up. My PC is not exactly what you'd call slow, but it takes phenomenal amounts of time to get past the game's loading screens. Considering that you need to go through that ordeal every time you want to fight a battle, and that battles are practically the sole focus of the game, this detracts massively from the overall experience. And while I call the game ""Tactical,"" this only really holds true playing against other human beings. The AI in this game is competent - clever, even - but nine games out of ten are almost guaranteed to have some kind of bug, whether that be running against a wall and never getting anywhere, not reliably counting as engaged in combat when fighting on or around stairs, or trying to get somewhere they simply will not fit.Despite this, however, the management and progression systems are well polished, the skill and equipment mechanics deep and interesting enough that you can spend hours customising your fighters to fit the roles you want, the injuries show up in all their gory detail on the character models, and the array of mutations available to Chaos warbands is a thing of absolute twisted beauty. I feel entirely satisfied by the breadth of customisation available in this game, and overall it does a superlative job of capturing the essence and character of the Warhammer universe.But when considering this game always bear in mind that I wrote this while waiting for a scenario to load.Edit 09/02/16: It bears mentioning that loading times have now been much improved. I would say that it's even quite quick, now, often finishing before the excellent loading screen voiceovers finish doing their thing."
