,Recommended,276810,29958867,Posted: 16 February,all,Telparion,"Quite deep once you have learnt the rpoes+ create your own warband, invest your gold, upgrade them as you see fit+ challenging gameplay: still getting defeats at times+ super-lengthy campaign: 50+ hours with the one same warband and still at Act I!+ different story, point of view, voice-overs, objectives with each warband+ randomized missions and events+ skills and progression become deeply interesting once at 1500+ rating, with plenty of options+ varied warbands and races, varied builds with any warrior (once at 1500+)+ interesting in PVE as a single player super-campaign, and in PVP- before: long loading times (so get a SSD, load lightning fast and ignore that problem!)- skills and progression become deeply interesting only at 1500+ rating, because you may be very puzzled before (I mean that I was)- before you understand that, the game looks as if it would just ""play on its own"" and people may find it either too easy or too difficult in the beginning- developing your warband needs timeI disagree with the luck problem some people mention but that needs further explanation:To win you cannot just engage a 70 % chance-to-hit warrior vs a 50 % warrior.A defeat on such circumstances is quite acceptable.Sure victory is earned by ambushing, retreating, not using all your Strategic Points at once... something I learnt the hard way after a few mistakes. You need to have warriors you can easily use as buffer and others to support the victory, to compensate for the occasionnal stun, etc. Overall fights then often unfold with some difficult episodes but nice story and tactics.More review:You begin by picking a warband, and on that part you have a lot of choices.Some warband have bow or gun fighters and one (the Sisters of Battle) start as a full melee warband with more and more range options thanks to spells later on.You have access to plenty of classes but some will be unlocked further down.Overall your warband begins with 5 warband-specific character classes for your party and can upgrade that to 8 classes and more.In itself, that unlocks many variations in how you build a warband. These variations are deepened further by injuries and every character progression.After digging the game more I discovered that even if you pick a single, simple objective for a character progression (ie: le's just make him or her a super dodger) there are no less than 7 skills to pick and upgrade for that objective, meaning you would only learn half of them over time. That's for one objective.. .imagine then if you mix that up ;)About the classes you have:You have access to one leader class; leaders can usually be upgraded in one role among many possible ones.You recruit henchmen from usually 2 specific henchmen classes.You recruit heroes from 2 (then 4 once your warband gets better) specific hero classes.You cannot bring more than 2 heroes of the same class, so must bring some varietyLater on you will unlock your Impressive character class. Impressives are a good way to counter an enemy Impressive, but they take two hero slots, so it's either an Impressive or two heroes, which is a hard choice.Last but certainly not least you occasionnaly can even add other races/faction classes to your warband depending on which faction you favored.BattleEvery day you can commit your warband to a battle making your choice on the map.You bring 10 warriors to the battlefield with others left at camp.Objectives are random.Warriors play turn by turn with the highest initiative (ie best Agility etc) beginning the turn.Every warrior can move and attack:they have Offense Points (red) to lead attacks and Strategic Points (blue) to lead other actions.At the end of your turn you can activate a ""Stance"" that would affect the enemy during his own turn (needs at least two blue points), and your left-over Offense points can also be used to strike back with ""counter attacks"" (usually needs at least two red points) or to set up an Ambush action. To ambush the enemy, the best move is not to be in an open area to prevent him from seeing you and charging you, but to use houses and indoor obstacles.You would not understand how to best use the tools you have during your first battles.Overall the game can be played as a no-brainer in the beginning, it is just that you'll also commit  a number of mistakes.Mistakes in the game are OK: you can lose a leg, an eye, a warrior... or even many. It doesn't need much gold to replace them. Also, by playing you also upgrade your ""Veteran skills"" which are warband achievements that unlock powers you'll carry over with your next warbands/campaigns.A great game, it needed time for me to understand its great qualities!Currently there is no game with such character progression variation.A pity it takes so much time to understand the depth and quality of the skills provided in game.Note that PVP matches are long however."
