,Recommended,276810,28477055,"Posted: 19 December, 2016",all,Schweetness101,"I played 20 hours in my first weekend with this game. So, it's safe to say that I'm enjoying myself.The turn-based combat is fun, challenging, balanced, and only iron-man style saved games. The artwork and world are warhammer of course, so no problems there. The rpg elements and the numbers behind them are all out in the open, and the options for customization and skills are varied, but not too overwhelming.Your soldiers can receive permanent injuries from being knocked out in combat, which comes with visual changes like scars, lost eyes, peg-legs, etc...The style of any given type of weapon is customized to not only the faction, but also the type of unit within the faction (e.g. 'helmet' not only looks different for, say, sisters of sigmar vs mercenaries, but also for hero champions vs henchmen warriors within mercenaries).There's some recycling of map assets, but there are enough different layouts, orientations, and starting points that you don't really mind, and the story missions add some interesting variety on top of the standard 'route the enemy while collecting wyrdstones'. Also, the reason you can't collect all of the wyrdstones after the battle is that a) you auto collect some and b) lore-wise your soldiers are withdrawing from a dangerous area after some of them were wounded, so they don't have time to scour the whole place (the more are alive after the battle, the more stones you get). Although, I will admit that it is an imperfect solution.I find that the UI in battle is pretty intuitive, and usable with only a few buttons, but i see that others have criticized it. to each his own i guess.Some cons:a little too much waiting for animations and two clicks where one should do. Also, sometimes I wish I could get one unit past another in a doorway, hallway or some other narrow space.Some of the 'impressive' units are kind of lame. I don't really like the artwork on the ogre, for instance.I'm not really sure what it is all building towards, and sometimes it seems like the story missions are too few and far between as compared with the normal missions.face textures can be pretty bad, especially the youngblood mercenary, who has a 'punchable' facetoo often i have like a 95% hit chance that misses twice in a row, what is that a 0.25% chance of happening?theres this animation of throwing both arms back and opening the mouth in a silent scream that happens with almost every action or stance change that feels like a placeholder that should have been replacedi wish i could move/deploy units from the overhead map modehard to tell topographic info from the overhead mapthe ai is fairly easy to beat once you figure them out, although i only choose the 'normal' difficulty missionshaven't found much of a good use for the warlocksome tedious, minute upgrading after each battle, and some skills and traits that seem worthlesssometimes RNG is annoying, but that goes with the territoryall of my guys are waiting on me getting enough money for their skill upgrades, which isn't going to happen. I have a dozen guys, each with a few skill points to spend by now, but it costs either 100 or 200 gp to buy each one, and after paying upkeep, medical, recruitment, and equipment costs, i can afford to buy like one skill for one warrior every wrydstone shipment request period (like every 10 game days, during which I'll probably do 5 missions, or like 3 hours of gameplay about)repetitive loading screen messagesA lot of these cons are the sort of number tweaking or minor adjustment type things that could be done in a single patch (e.g. fix RNG percent chances, drastically lower skills gold costs, speed up or get rid of some animations, write more loading screen quotes, make some better face textures, allow deployment from tactical map, etc...), and I'd like to hope that they will be fixed in an upcoming update, although I have no idea about that.The comparisons to XCOM are inevitable, and generally unfavorable to Mordheim judging by the other reviews, but for what it's worth I played XCOM 2 for a couple hours before getting a bit bored/frustrated and moving on (temporarily, I'll give it another try later), but I played 20 hours basically straight of Mordheim the first weekend I fired it up, so take from that what you will.This is one of those games that is flawed, but very fun and keeps me coming back, like mount and blade, rome total war, and men of war (i don't mean that it's like those mechanically, of course)"
