76561197977295842,Not Recommended,276810,23973894,"Posted: 30 June, 2016",all,PsychoThruster,"Only pick this up on sale. I really enjoy the basic gameplay but am dissapointed by the severe lack of customization options, ugly character models, and poor animations. Considering the turn based nature and lack of action oriented gameplay it should be rather easy to create nice pre-canned animations, but instead they remind of an mmo decades past. Minimal effort put in. The animations for ranged attacks are the worst of the bunch because they don't pitch up or down. For the price they normally ask for this product and considering when this was released I expect much better.Edit: It is also worth mentioning that the graphics advertised are not what I have actually experienced despite system specs which can handle the game twice over and having all settings at maximum the game looks quite poor and more like a 2009 release. This may be due to the fact that I have AMD and apparently this game has trouble with AMD. So beware of that if you too have an AMD card. Highly frustrating not being able to enjoy the graphics.The DLC is a complete ripoff and incredibly lazy in it's implimentation. They could not even be bothered to create one faction specific unit for each faction so two of the four are shared between factions. The new Witch Hunters faction is incredibly ugly, their primary units are so despressing to look at, yet if they could be customized to a greater extent this could perhaps be forgiven, but it seems this newest faction has even fewer customization options than the others. Hope you like having anorexic, half naked, self-flagellation obsessed old men as the backbone of your fighting force! I get that it's cannon, but the execution is quite poor. It's the lack of variation in appearence and the fact that the vision the developers had far exceeds religious flagellation and takes a turn into chaos level self mutilation. It's overdone. Also there's no hounds... no ♥♥♥♥ing hounds.Edit: The dlc is even worse than I initially thought because any army of order can use the human dlc heroes and any army of destruction can use the skaven and chaos dlc heroes. The joy of a game like this is the asymetric balance, letting units move from one warband to another kills that and it really makes me never want to take part in pvp. So despite owning these special units I never use them because it cheapens the experience and breaks immersion. Why they could not develop one special unit for each warband and release it as one character pack is beyond me, but if many more units are added in this way you'll start seeing primarily mercenary warbands in pvp that have little connection to their actual warband. Already too many wolf priest builds going around as it is. Really really bad design choice on part of the developers. Asymetric balance is key in a game like this and every deviation from it will kill the experience a little more.The gameplay itself is pretty fun and does a decent job capturing the feel of a tabletop game for the most part. Unfortunately it's bogged down by a grind oriented campaign that has you doing the same thing over and over and over. There are a few different scenarios, but that merely changes how you deploy, not the objective which is to eliminate or route the opposing team. Story missions change it up a bit, but not enough to make it feel fresh. And while there is a pvp component that ought to be fun, it's just more of the same. It lacks the fun social element of a tabletop experience. Also playing the pvp mode that enables injuries and looting is a huge risk considering the intensive grind that goes into getting decent units, and the safe mode is without risk or reason to play, though you may learn a trick or two.I like the hardcore element, but leveling up is far too arduous. I think the most frustrating element is that you can rarely complete secondary objectives for their xp boost because the enemy team routes and essentially ends the round. Thus any unclaimed salvage, unclaimed loot, and unclaimed wyrdstone dissapears. Sure you get a few bones for a victory, but it's pitance in comparison. Furthermore this makes no sense. If they ran away, why not let me get everything? What's stopping me? Why make me game the system and spend three hours emptying a map only to realize that doing so is insane and a total bore. Fixing this issue alone might go a long way towards making the game feel less like a grind.The game needs some fresh ideas and a strong multiplayer component if it wants to have any real staying power, right now it's one of those titles you buy on sale, play for a week or two and then forget about. It's a real shame too because this game does have potential. The underlying mechanics are sound for the most part, but everything built off of them needs to be reconsidered.Bottom line: If you are interested in this title and enjoy turn based gameplay then snag it next time it drops below $20. However you'll most likely regret spending anything more than that."
