76561197986670728,Recommended,276810,33745412,Posted: 23 July,all,HoveringBeef,"Took me about 80 hours to beat the Witch-Hunters campaign, no idea if that's average, but I do like to rampage.The game is hard but mostly forgiving, in my playtime I think I've only had 5 or 6 warriors die, though one was my highest ranked leader when I had to abort a campaign mission due to being trapped by a bug.I've fired a couple of cripples who had head injuries too, had 2 priests get insta-smited by the 9999dmg backfire (both survived with no injuries) and seen it happen to the AI once.It's a tough game but if you stick with it, it does get better. The campaign missions can be a lot of back and forth to complete objectives, enemy impressives seem to have pathing issues (rat ogre and the chaos thing are too large to move easily), and I've seen a fair few enemies stay up on a ledge going into ambush stance every turn instead of trying to walk a short distance to join the fight. AI also won't sacrifice a unit to block a path or tie enemies up, so I'd say you always have the advantage (as long as you keep line of sight for your ranged units)I have a Templar with I think around 106% parry chance, so he was total cheese when he's fighting 3 or 4 enemies at once, evading or parrying everything, immune to fear/terror/all alone tests and slowly grinding them down while the rest of my team swarms the enemy. Except Chaos mutants, who wear bracers that prevent parrying, but there's a lot of little things you learn as you play that make it easier (like spells or ranged attacks that cause a bleed type effect).Optional objectives can be a chore, but then they're optional, and for the reward (3xp and 3 random loot items) usually not worth the risk.Definitely a game that rewards planning over aggression, it's pretty slow but at least you can ""speed up AI turn"" in the options. I played about 7 hours originally and then didn't touch it for a year, so I guess they patched that in."
