76561198007375920,Recommended,276810,26588606,"Posted: 13 November, 2016",all,Caveman,"Mordheim, a game I have been playing on and off since early access, is a nice game turn based tactical game - resembling x-com, bloodbowl and other games where you have movement points and fighting points. You will get to know the characters of your warband, develop them and style them. But futher no real stretegic support of your party. You can insert character history and slighty modify their looks. I always like building up.However... the game is also quite merciless. My brave band of imperial mercenaries is led by a one-legged captain, assisted by a one-legged hero; covered by a archer with a permanent open wound; I have to admit. In other games I might have saved my sacred band of brave warriors and my twin-sister smugglers quite often and would have reloaded the missions time and time again to cheat my way out of the leg-losing and thus would have prevented the limitation of the range and actions of my beloved Captain Kenrick and his sidekick the couragrous hero Havok Sparrenschild. I would have re-loaded to avoid the loss of fighting points for my carefully contructed 6th level sharpshooter 'Lars Genade'. But alas. The loss is forever and final.... So much better this paralympic approach to find the green magical shards that are scattered throughout the city.Ofcourse you have to like the warhammer world to like the game, which is sometime a bit repetitious (but I didn't mind). If you can't stand skaven and ogres... don't buy this game. But if you feel like rampaging with blunderbusses and warhammers through a rotten, deserted, corrupted and decaying city (the artwork is quite nice): it is worth buying. Just be aware that you have to seperately buy the DLC.  That might be the true curse of Sigmar's comet."
76561197991773070,Recommended,276810,24744174,"Posted: 6 August, 2016",all,Hooded Justice,"Mordheim is a rather challenging turn-based squad management RPG set in the Warhammer world, with unforgiving rogue-like qualities that won't be to eveyone's liking. To be quite frank, people who head in thinking Mordheim willl be akin to XCOM will probably be rather let down. This is primarliy an old Games Workshop board game brought to life with all the idiosyncracies this entails, and it therefore has far more in common with Blood Bowl than regular turn-based titles. Don't let the 3rd person gfx trick you into thinking otherwise, that's basically just a way of getting scenary and elevation changes to work (something that wasn't needed with Cyanide's Blood Bowl conversion).The Blood Bowl comparisons continue through to the front-end, which is about as user friendly as a casual headbutt. However, perseverance with the steep learning curve and the obtuse management system does start to pay off. Trying to keep a fledgling warband afloat by selling everything and fielding guys with smashed up legs only to find you've then got no spare weapons for your next raid is the kind of experience you'll either like or despise - luckily for me, it's right up my street.I tried PVP in beta and it had a lot going for it but I've just been doing campaign stuff since I fired it up aagin and I am genuinely impressed with the solo experience. The meta actually has a lot in common with Darkest Dungeon (this is a good thing, DD is wonderful). Also of note is that the Xbox pad works nicely, meaning I can get my tactical on from the armchair.Mordheim has developed nicely into a game that now offers a fairly singular experience, though undoubtably rather niche. If you're looking for a mixture of Blood Bowl and Darkest Dungeon then look no further."
76561198091067271,Recommended,276810,20637466,"Posted: 19 January, 2016",all,TheWayfaring,"Mordheim: City of the Damned is an infuriating, venom-dripping, and chaotic experience. However, it is an altogether pleasant experience and game.Mordheim: CotD is a turn-based video game adapation of the tabletop Mordheim gameset in the Warhammer Fantasy universe, where the goal is to survive a hellish landscape in order to gather a rare, and dangerous, material known as Wyrdstone, known for its chaotic influence and ability to enhance magic. Being set in the more turbulent era of Warhammer Fantasy history, there is an abundance of weapons to use that are unique, magic with consequences, strict limitations and possible firing zones with ranged weapons (of which there are bows and firearms), and mythical races of characters. While this game does not have all of the races from the older Mordheim, the four chosen are very different and give a very accurate (read: grimdark) feel for the setting.The four racesin CotD are the Empire Mercenaries, Skaven, Cult of the Possessed, and the Sisters of Sigmar. These races are divided into Warbands, consisting of (as time goes on) one Leader unit, up to three Hero units, one Impressive unit, and five Henchmen units. Following will be a generalization of each race, their purpose, and then a general playstyle (though this game is nearly limitless with how you create your Warband, and how you play them, especially with injuries being added into the mix). Spoilers will be placed for storyline, although only very vague information is given.The Empire Mercenaries are a warband of human mercenaries from the proud coalition of human factions.The Empire Mercenaries are part of the Order alignment, implying good intentions and care for the world.The mercenaries are sent to gather Wyrdstone for their employer. They do not care about his reasons.Mercenaries generally rely on tankier melee units and higher damage ranged units. Amazing in a team, this warband has issues if separated, for a ranged character is helpless if ambushed in melee, and will die from a few hits, while a melee character lacks the damage to best his opponent, leaving them locked in combat for several turns.The Skaven are a race of greedy and cruel humanoid rat-men, particularly from Clan Eshin, a clan of assassins.The Skaven are part of the Chaos alignment, working for selfish intentions and care little for anybody but themselves.The Skaven warband is attempting to gather Wyrdstone, which they call Warpstone, in order to increase personal prestige among the ranks of the influential Murderlord.The Skaven are low health with high Initiative (order of who goes first per turn) and high damage. They generally rely on quickly swarming an enemy (one of their racial skills, appropriately named Swarm, gives bonuses for every Skaven attacking the same unit) and wiping them out one or two at a time. Lacking any tanks until they get their Impressive rank warrior, they rely on Dodging and Parrying even more than the other races.The Cult of the Possessed are a faction of mutants and chaos warriors with no regard for life at all.The Cult is a Chaos-aligned faction, willing to murder and betray, and even mutate their own bodies, for more power.The Cult is attempting to obtain greater and greater power from an entity known as the Shadowlord, in exchange for Wyrdstone.The Cult is generally a more melee oriented unit, though they have a Magician as their Leader, and rely on overwhelming power to kill their foes. Lots of buffs, decent health, and high damage make them a force to be reckoned with, especially in the scarily narrow streets of Mordheim.The Sisters of Sigmar are a zealous group of religious fanatics, similar to Paladins from other games.The SoS are aligned with Order, hoping to combat evil and to spread the message of their god through face-smashing.The SoS are attempting to gather all of the Wyrdstone simply so that it cannot fall into the hands of evil.The SoS generally rely on powerful and high health units to completely destroy their enemies in combat. However they are slow, and have a very difficult time dealing with multi-level attacks.Mordheim is a very dangerous placeoften causing injuries to your Warband ranging from a simple experience loss, to amputation, and death. The game is very unforgiving, and you may make two or three Warbands, having them be crippled and ruined one after the other, until something finally clicks and you surge ahead, destroying your opposition and doingSOgood until your main warrior loses an arm, and can no longer use that bow/halberd/shield that you relied on, and you scream into the night, causing dogs to bark, and you fume and pace around your room trying to decide if you should get a new Leader, make a new Warband, or accept the 20% dodge increase from losing an arm, and you just keep rambling and crying and pout... sorry, that hit a little close to home. As a game of incredibly high risk though, the RNG is downright out to get you, and you will often miss attacks you had an 85% chance to hit. Twice. This may seem unfair, however it is more accurately tied to the tabletop game where you'd roll upwards of five die per attack. Yet, even with an AI you swear is cheating, your best warrior being taken down by a stupid ambush that you totally weren't in range of, and RNG causing you to lose your best tank because he missed a 97% parry chance, victory is insanely addicting.Mordheim: CotD, despite being brutal and unfair, is one of the few games I've played in a long time that really made my victories feel hard-fought and well-earned. I'm addicted to finding out what I could do, and could have done, better. 8/10TL;DR: Hard game, lots of customization, game literally hates you, you may want to amputate your own limbs (I mean, hey, 20% bonus dodge chance!). Awesome."
