76561197984892423,Recommended,276810,29785569,Posted: 8 February,all,Muscarine,"Gonna throw my thumbs inMordheim is a great game well worth its price and your time, although it will not necessarily fit all types of player profiles.Do not even try if you're the kind of players who build their entire strategy around the idea that percentage equals luck i.e ""i missed 5x 80% in a row CHEAT !"".If you do understand, on the other hand that the worst thing you can do in RNG games is to try your luck, and that you should instead build to mitigate bad outcomes, then by all means this game is a delight.If you just roll the dice you're bound to get lucky or unlucky, but that's the whole point with RNG games, don't try to get lucky.So you can reroll until everyone crits on the first round, or you can find one of the many strategies at your disposal that will work 95% of the time.You're going to spend a lot of time before your characters sheets brainstorming builds, synergies and party compositions, if you don't have the patience for it then you will get your booty spanked.To that effect i highly recommend you get comfortable using this build planner :http://www.pyrospace.co.uk/mordheim/considering the game itself doesn't give crucial informations it should have, in my opinion, such as basic important values like how many skill points can a unit have at cap.The very beginning of the game when all your recruits are fresh is extremely rough since there's no real synergie and you will have to rely on lucky rolls, but that's how it starts and after you begin piling up money and experience everything starts clicking together.There will be casualties.There will be mission failures.But your Warband stands and you can only move forward.Eventually you will grow more and more comfortable and aside from the occasionnal KO units, failure will become history.Mordheim does have issues : unintuitive UI, bugs creeping in at the worst time, a general feeling of lacking that last pass of polishing. The tutorials are very helpful but don't really cover every decisive mechanics.But it's gritty, unforgiving, and deeply satisfying.I have one real issue with the game overall, the way AI is handled put together with seldom punishing bad rolls successions.See, the AI doesn't really act like a Warband with a hive mind as yours will since you control everything, they're more like independant suicidal drones going in a bee line for any kill they can grab no matter if they get slaughtered in the process.This lack of refinement will sometimes lead to the demise of some of your units like a vessel sinking under the weight of countless kamikaze crashing themselves on it, one after another.While it can lead to some frustrating experiences it's not a real issue as long as you understand that the narrator doesn't ask ""Who among us will die today"" just to be cute.All in all a great addition to your library as long as you are a player made of iron, and don't really enjoy make believe sugar coated feel good designs."
,Recommended,276810,29638810,Posted: 1 February,all,vex,"I am both surprised and not surprised to find this game has mixed reviews. What's more surprising is that a lot of the negative reviews are from people familiar with the tabletop game it was adapted from.I was a big Mordheim fan in my teenage years despite not having much affection for Games Workshop's more popular products. I loved how it mixed role-playing, which I was a big fan of, and war games. It really felt like a tabletop XCOM.I hate to say that people nixing this game are playing it wrong, but they are. Your warband is not meant to be eternal. While I think it's a bit of a design hiccup to add a campaign mode, thus the illusion of progression, but the Mordheim I remember isn't about that. It's about seeing how far you can get before you run your warband into the ground. Once you've done that, you're meant to roll up the next warband.You're not meant to form any kind of bond or attachment to your individual actors. They're tools. In time, they will wear out and break. If you have the gold, you replace them with fresh tools. If you don't, you go out of business. It's that simple.And while there really isn't a lot of variety to the combat in the early stages of the game...generally it pays to bait the AI into an ambush then gang up on them before help arrives...I don't mind because that's generally how Mordheim always worked. Your individual fighters are so brittle and weak, and risking them can be very costly, combat is all about managing the risk/reward of individual engagements. It's about setting up kill zones to lure enemies into where your best assets are covered by henchmen and efficiently knocking enemies out of the fight.I only wish maps were either larger or the AI a little less aggressive so that it would be possible to grab more of the wyrdstone and treasure on the map. Unlike the tabletop game, most of your income comes from items collected during the mission rather than rewarded after the fact.In all, if you enjoy games like XCOM but want something a little more brutal that requires a bit more patience and time to learn, I wholeheartedly recommend Mordheim."
76561197991722289,Recommended,276810,13035309,"Posted: 21 November, 2014",all,The Guide,"This game has a lot of potential, but as a very early access title it's lacking a *lot* of content at the moment. The base combat system is easy enough to grasp (though the keyboard controls feel clunky at times) yet still hints at a lot of depth in gameplay. I'm really looking forward to seeing what they do with the single player campaign/warband progression.The game captures the world and atmosphere of Warhammer Fantasy quite well with good character and level models/textures. I did notice that a failed climb-down animation using a Sister parted her torso from her legs a bit and exposed the nothingness inside, but it's early access and that's only a small visual bug.The only gameplay bug I encountered was on the Temple of Sigmar map, skirmishing against AI and playing as the defender in the siege scenario. It took me a few turns to realise what was happening as I had no idea where the AI team was - they were trapped outside and didn't seem capable of getting in (which I think required climbing) so it would have been up to the defender to exit and engage the enemy.Given the newness I have no idea how good (or bad) the company is at updating and sticking to schedule etc., so can't comment on that yet. Looking forward to playing more as the updates come. The game is definitely worth keeping an eye on even if you're not interested in playing the early access (which I usually avoid, but I'm a fan of WHFB so I couldn't wait for this)."
