,Recommended,276810,26426302,"Posted: 4 November, 2016",all,easterngames,"THE BEST PC GAMES YOU NEVER PLAYED (AND SHOULD) REVIEW SERIESOne the best games out there if you are into turn based games and or Warhammer fantasy world setting.The average person will get about 200 hours out of this game along with the DLC already available. And you will want the DLC. With witchunters, the smuggler, and the poison globe skaven being my favorites. Even if you dont buy the DLC's they will still show up in your game as enemies. So really its all free unless you want to play them yourself.This game is unforgiving and brutal. The learning curve will have you swearing and pulling out your hair. You can not manually save and if you screw up, your warband will pay for it in crippled or dead troops. You can manually cheat and save your games, but id suggest not as you risk corrupting the save file and losing it all. If you are used to save scumming and just taking back all your mistakes, then you will be rather annoyed with this game. AT least until you learn its generally ok to take a beating and unless you totally bite it three times in a row, then you can recover from a bad round or two.Some quick hints for new players:Keep your band together, dont try to one on one fight the enemies. Choose missions where your warband all starts around your wagon.Choose early on to what defense type you will use, being either dodge or parry type and seek out skills you can learn later on that allow you to use these defenses twice in a turn.Its ok to skip a day to let your team heal from injuries or train skills. Its not the end of the world to skip a day.Story missions are impossibly hard, well so it may seem. Make sure you are ready before diving in.This game has a good selection of warbands right now, but it really could use more. And hopefully there will be more ASAP. The table top version has so many options and in comparison the PC version feels a bit lacking. But 7 like the game has now is a decent enough selection of warbands. And they all have different play styles which makes it even better. But personally i wouldn't mind 14 of them, with each main warband re-skinned in a slightly different variant.The leveling system is addicting. The loot is just varied enough to be addicting, though i wish there were more to choose from on some warbands. Some warbands use rather specialized gear and it can be hard sometimes to find upgraded versions of it from all the random drops. The wolf priest being the prime example, i have never once found an upgraded version of his enhanced weapon of ulric.All in all this game will give you your monies worth. And hopefully in the future DLCs will up the ante even more. Its a total buy and if you find this game on sale and dont buy it, THEN SLAP YOURSELF! cause youre making a huge mistake not getting it.(also available on consoles if that is your thing)"
76561198002911957,Recommended,276810,29861453,Posted: 11 February,all,LORD OF THE HARVEST,"As I dig this wyrd tick from my skin with the tip of my rusty dagger, I ponder why I traveled to Mordheim in the first place...nearly everyone I traveled with to this blasted city has died or disappeared. The weather is nearly as tempermental as the food and I've faced horrors I never wish to speak of or think of again.It seems whenever we strike a find of wyrsdstone or long lost gear, we lose someone to some thing. It is completely unfair...We hired an ogre once, Four-Tooth Tubbygut. We thought things would ge easier...we were wrong. The blasted bellower just attracted worse things. I remember that day well, I lost an eye and Heinrech...lost his life and let me tell you, losing a man while you're staring down the blood red, dead, eyes of a vampire is something you quickly won't forget.Sure, Ace McTwirlystache may make a shot that cripples one of those vile mutants allowing you and the gang to cease its diabolical existence but those moments seem to be so few and far inbetween. Everytime I look up to our leader Maximillion I realize it's Hubert Steinbor-...no wait it's Von Drakham, no wait it's someone fresh.Ha! Fresh blood in Mordheim, the only constant...again I ask myself why I first agreed to sign up for this damned company. Gold? Glory? Riches?Now that I think about it...I remember exactly why I signed up for this.*Thus ends the ramblings of Emrich the peg legged, one eyed, one armed wyrdstone gatherer*To the point. This is a brutal game. It is unforgiving and the odds are stacked against you. I would say this is less of a ""RNG game"" than it is a ""how you adjust and react to a problematic situations"". I say this simply because you will be faced with many rough situations.It's similar to Valkyria Chronicles with movement and the actions use a action point system in a sense as well. Many who jump into the game never come back because it's tough, it has a steep learning curve but just remember the Warband is what matters.Do not get attached to characters. They. Will. Die. They will get maimed and nigh useless. You will be forced into making decisions where their is no ""good"" outcome but ""which is less worse"".The warbands, and their are 6, play differently and have a different feel. Weapons balance is wonderful because a daggr can be just as useful, if not more so, than a halbred. A bow better than a handgun, it is up to you to figure out when it is best to use a certain weapon as well as how to build a character around a certain weapon. This game requires you to laugh when things go bad and to learn so you lower the chance of making the same mistake again (because honestly you will make that same mistake again).The story missions, which each warband has their own, are tough and should be tackled after you spend a decent amount of time learning the basics and gearing your warband out. They aren't amazingly done and honestly, they can be quite frustrating but they do break up the normal gameplay of warband fights and wyrdstone hunting.The AI is adequate and even though they do one of the largest pet peeves I have with video games (artificial difficulty by giving the AI stat buffs, depending upon the difficulty) it's fun. The AI matches its warband to yours, so if you bring a big guy they do, if you don't they don't. This way you can't rest on your heels with an all decked out warband, the opposing warband will always be a threat.Ultimately, the game has some flaws but I believe it is a game worth playing for a certain type of gamer. One that tackles a challenge expecting to learn something. Those who go in as an underdog who appreciates when they make a 30% hit 2 times in a row. Those willing to take chances for a big payout, at the cost of possibly suffering complete failure.As with most games, I recommend getting it on sale."
