76561197997771830,Not Recommended,276810,28964244,Posted: 2 January,all,archon989,"My review of Mordheim: City of the DamnedI believe a rating system of 1-5 would be better than the binary yes/no Steam uses.  Overall I would rate this game somwhere near 2.5.  Since there is not, I would have to not recommend this game.The pros and cons:Pros:Immersive worldGood musicWarhammerGame-to-game advancementCons:Based mostly on randomnessShallow gameplayPoor balanceTo summarize, Mordheim is a squad-based game in which you complete missions to varying degrees of success in order to loot the remains of the city of Mordheim.  The game feels fairly tabletop-ish with most mechanics based on measures and die-rolls.  There is an advancement and permanent-ish injury system which leads to unique gameplay situations.  Overall I found all this as appealing, particularly considering this is set in the Warhammer universe.  Going game-to-game and playing for not just the moment but the next several as well in a post-apocalyptic warhammer world.Why I cannot recommend this game, however, is disappointing.  There are 6 factions available right now including DLC.  Considering the majority of missions revolve around one side retreating, these factions are not close to balanced.  The game has a definite hierarchy of concerning the difficulty of factions.  At the top, the easiest and therefore toughest factions are the Sisters of Sigmar and the Undead.  Slow but physically dominant factions.  In a rough order following those 2 are the Skaven, Human Mercenaries, Witch Hunters, and Cult of the Possessed.  Worse now, is that there are minimal differences between each of them as the game progress.All factions consist of 1 leader, 3 hero options, 1 prestige class, and 2 henchmen.  All classes have their own attributes, proficiences (which dictate gear), spells, and somewhat different skills.  Skills are mostly shared across all classes and are based on statistics.  Attributes are capped based on class but not that significantly.  Spells are the most significant difference between classes as either you have access to Divine or Arcane or neither.  The combination of these 4 facets differentiate classes.  This means that through advancement most classes can match others.  I find this rather undesirable as a caster can be as proficient physically as most melee classes.  This lends itself to the Sisters and Cult being rather better in the longer-game.  I have the Cult lower mostly because they start as the whipping boys that you are glad to see as your opponent early in campaigns.  Not to mention the fact that the devs somehow thought that giving the Sisters a normal-sized prestige class was somehow balanced.I bought the game on significant sale which made it mostly worth.  Hopefully further content will be released which expands upon variety.  I wouldn't spend more than $20 on it as it currently stands.  I feel most people looking for a challenge will end up at the same point I am at.  The game is either too easy or unskillfully difficult which leads to boredom."
76561198073328826,Recommended,276810,31079792,Posted: 11 April,all,captainthorrek,"Mordheim: City of the Damned is a great game based off Games Workshop's Tabletop skirmish game.  If you're looking for a direct translation, this is not the game for you.  If you want a great tactical skirmish and management game, this should be on your wishlist.The important part is to keep both sides of the game in balance: tactical and management.  Your Warband can quickly find itself out of money if you lose matches, or get your Warband members skills without a cushion.  Adding Wyrdstone shipments to the mix, and you have an adequate representation of life in Mordheim.  It may not be true to the game, but it has Mordheim's spirit down.While playing against the AI is fun, it's even better when you are playing against a human opponent... although one might be hard to come by at tmes.  You can do both with the same game, switching back and forth as your friends hop on, or playing against the computer to get that last bit of Wyrdstone in before the shipment's late (miss three and the game's over).There is one piece of advice before playing against human opponents: get used to playing against the computer first.  The game is frustrating when you start out, as you don't know the lay of the land that well.  True to its namesake, Mordheim is merciless when someone doesn't know the layout of each map as well as their opponent.  You will find yourself flanked, and a great skirmish game will find itself shelved.Manage your Troops.  Manage your Gold.  Manage your Time.  Manage your Temper.  Do all these things, and you might survive Mordheim... for a while."
,Not Recommended,276810,30733700,Posted: 25 March,all,Putin Stronk,"This game has been in a number of states over its development but at the moment is still poor in many of the base mechanics and now is unbalanced. I've played a fair amount of tabletop and this is nothing like it, a brave move but one that i think didn't pay off. In tabletop you fight the battles and then afterwards did the exploration phse for wyrdstone. The game combines the two, this sucks as 1. the exploration phase was one of the best parts of mordheim and 2. It feels every time you go looking for wyrdstone you run in to someone else's warband making it feel like there's a warband in every house, not a deserted city. The mechanics have a lot of problems as well. First of all guessing measurements, AI getting stuck on doors and a number of other problems with the janky movement suggest to me at least a rough grid system would've helped massively. The map design doesn't help one bit with plenty of bits for the AI to derp around on and design that can leave each warband just wandering around collecting bits for several turns with no reason to fight and slowing down a system that drags on anyway. The recent addition of undead and witch hunters have unbalanced the game significantly. WH are fine but the undead are massivley unbalanced (dregs were designed in tabletop to help exploration and not much else where as here they're equvilent of merc champions) Zombies have a ridiculously high initiative and the same pace as regular humans. The vampires themselves could do with a buff however as again they only really have the same stats as a human captain, a bit disappointing for whats supposed to be a supernatural killing machine.Overall I as a long time fan of Mordheim am very disappointed with this game and while its fun for a while frustration at the issues sets in. I'm still hopefull they might iron this out and it has come a long way from the early days but all in all still not a good game quite yet"
,Not Recommended,276810,21507280,"Posted: 27 February, 2016",all,KaioShin,"I really want to love this game, but I just can't in good conscious recommend it to anyone. There are too many issues.In case you aren't aware, Mordheim is based on a skirmish tabletop by Games Workshop, though as I understand it it doesn't use the original game's rules. The adaption is a turn based strategy game in a really dark fantasy setting where you build and manage a warband. You recruit heroes and henchmen and slowly build them up by surviving randomly generated missions. There are permanent consequences anywhere, from permanent injuries after dying to downright permadeath. There is a constant race against time too since you need to deliver a ressource in time that you can gather during missions every few ingame weeks. If you manage to do it the timer is reset, but if you don't the whole game is lost. Losing too many people permanently and not being able to go to missions to gather the ressource does in essence also lose you the game permanently. This doesn't happen after 3 or 4 hours by the way, this will become a problem after 20 or 30 hours.It would all be fine if it would all be down to your skill as a player, but there is a TON of reliance on RNG in this game. If facing permanent debilitations because of things completely outside your control is something that bothers you, dear god stay away from this game.But it wasn't what made me quit playing ultimately (no I didn't ragequit after losing the game). What kills it is the slowness. There is a ton of waiting for enemy actions during missions and slow animations that can't be skipped or sped up. Also, the story missions are absolutely terribly designed. They are on maps that are confusing as heck with totally unclear mission directions. And they take forever. The first try you are almost guaranteed to lose until you figure out what the mission is even about. They are just a complete drag and no fun at all. After 20 hours of building my warband, seeing the forth mission of the sisterhood and thinking that I will have to face more of that♥♥♥♥♥♥after 20 more hours I just lost all energy and motivation.Thanks but no thanks, there are games that are simply more fun than this."
76561198035893605,Not Recommended,276810,34922643,Posted: 13 September,all,deornwulf,"The game design sets players up for failure. Enemy warbands have infinite resources and have no need to scavenge or collect wyrdstones, allowing the computer to operate under different tactics than the resource limited player. You are given the choice of immediately going on the defensive to attempt to destroy the enemy and miss out on collecting vital resources or vainly attempt to run around collecting stuff only to watch your warband be destroyed, one by one.The game definitely does NOT put the player on a level playing field with the computer opponents."
76561198130714472,Not Recommended,276810,33733282,Posted: 22 July,all,nherron831,"Pros:Turn based version of the Witcher if your into that sort of thing.The huge degree of specialization enables you to build teams to fit your styleWatching your characters modify over time via injuries (usually a really bad thing) forces you to adapt and adjust your style, making matchups a bit more interesting.Cons:The terrain in this game is laughably poorly constructed, making it nearly impossible to use the terrain advantage. I lost one match because the two leaders were fighting, and the angle prevented my hero from joining in combat against their leader, enabling him to kill my leader, and wipe me out.The triggers for ambushes are very poorly designed, but computers can ""Trap"" you into an ambush. I placed my character in an ambush outside a doorway, and the AI walked right past it, and set up an ""ambush"" right next to my character, ensuring i would be attacked next turn.The movement mechanism in this game tethers your units to multiple nodes in your walking trail, rather than checking the radius from your origin point. This makes it literally impossible to maximize your units mobility, while the AI is free to run the full gamut, and ensure maximal position advantage.AI take forever to make their moves. This make each game take forever to progress through, and there's no payoff for waiting through it when you lose.Ultimately, these issues make the game unwieldy, random, and slow. For hardcore fans of these chess-like xcom games, it might be worth the 10 bucks, but they lost my vote."
