76561197978543242,Recommended,276810,29882324,Posted: 12 February,all,wds_ncs,"Extremely satisfying tactical game saddled with a couple of questionable design decisions and a few lingering UI annoyances. Probably my favorite squad level tactics game released in years.Fans of tactics games can and should just buy and play it, but people considering buying might want to know what those cons I mentioned are. Above all, Mordheim TT players might be disappointed with some of the changes to the rules; I think they largely made smart changes, but purists should adjust their expectations. As for what I consider drawbacks in brief:The decision to have the AI build a team that mirrors yours is questionable. Every unit has a point value based on its abilities, skills, and equipment. You can field 4 to 10 units of varying tiers--leader, hero, henchman and impressive (a special unit)--in every battle. Their combined point value is your warband rating for a battle. When you go into battle, you select from a pool of missions with randomly generated difficulties--Normal, Hard, Brutal, or Deadly. The AI then generates an opposing team that exactly mirrors the composition of your team in number and tier with a warband rating equal to or exceeding yours, with % bonuses based on difficulty.For example, if I select a Brutal battle with five units--a leader, two heroes, and two henchmen, rating 1000--I will face an enemy band of five with a rating a bit higher than mine. They will all have +20% health and +15% damage due to difficulty rating.There are multiple consequences to this decision. The most notable to first time players is that there are no real ""milk run"" missions to let you learn the ropes. In the first week of a campaign, a combination of fragile low level units, player inexperience, and lack of resources with which to recover from losses means a huge difficulty hurdle. A full party wipe at this point is likely and a wipe means a game restart, given the game's ironman sensibility. The devs have attempted to remedy this by including several fairly good tutorials, that new players should probably play until they can win them, and with a universal experience system--in short, in game achievements can help you start the game with more advantages when starting new campaigns.Another is the effect this approach has on the sense of progression. Since ordinary battles scale, levelling your units and getting better equipment can feel a little Sysiphean. You will still always be quite outmatched, mechanically, on Deadly missions, whether you're deploying four rank 0 noobs or ten rank 10 veterans. The only exception are the eight story missions, unique to each faction, which have fixed difficulties. I personally feel the game would have benefited from creating districts containing increasingly difficult missions and better rewards and allowing you to complete missions in different areas. The upside to this, though, is that it keeps the game from feeling grindy. You will have enjoyably challenging battles at any point in the campaign and I never feel like I need to grind levels or drops in order to be able to tackle new challenges.The last consequence is a lack of variety due to the symmetry. You won't have battles where your leader and three heroes fight off a Skaven zerg rush; fielding a leader and six henchmen is always a fairly safe strategy, because your enemy will never decide to take an impressive against that composition. Even skirmishes (vs. other players) don't allow that flexibility.Another questionable design decision is the implementation of optional objectives and routs. Optional objectives include gathering a certain number of wyrdstones, the game's primary resource; killing specific enemies and taking trophies from them; or raiding the enemy's cart (their homebase of sorts) and carrying their ""flag"" back to yours. Routing, shortly, occurs when the morale value (I'll spare you the full explanation) of enemies left in action falls below 40% of its starting value and the highest ranked member of the enemy band left standing fails a leadership ability test. Completing optional objectives ultimately becomes a game of keeping the enemy alive long enough to let you complete the objective, since killing them wantonly may trigger a rout. In a sense, the game can feel like it punishes you for fighting effectively, ultimately generating you less experience and less loot.Lastly, the UI annoyances have been well documented elsewhere. I'll reiterate a short list: you must sit through enemy turns in real time, even if you can't see them, sometimes resulting in several minutes where you just twiddle your thumbs; LoS rules are not always intuitive; your units' zone of control (through which enemies cannot pass) or their occupied space (through which your own units cannot pass) is not viewable while you're positioning them, meaning you will inadvertently cut off routes for friendlies or leave paths through your line to your mages/ranged units open; pre-battle deployment of your units means cycling through the entire list of possible locations rather than just selecting them directly; where you can climb up and jump down isn't always displayed (inconsistently, it sometimes only displays them if the currently selected unit has enough movement points to jump or climb); the order of the different defensive stances (you'll only be good at one if you're playing correctly) changes randomly at times; warband management has a consolized interface requiring you to go down too many levels in order to change minor things.So, I've ♥♥♥♥♥ed at length about things in this game yet still recommend it. That's because the core of the game is that ♥♥♥♥ing entertaining. Buy it, git gud, have fun."
,Recommended,276810,29912225,Posted: 13 February,all,Reddragon,Great game
