,Recommended,276810,20963378,"Posted: 4 February, 2016",all,Nyttelost,"This will be lengthy, as I had plenty of time to write this while I download Patch 3 slowly because my internet connection sucks terribly. Also, my computer's terrible, but that's besides the point. Anyway, hold on tight.PreludeI grew up with a game calledWarhammer: Shadow of the Horned Rat. I had the PS1 version of the game, and for some reason I only had half of the instruction manual for the game. I had gotten the game from a yard sale of a neighbor who was moving and wanted some cash, presumably to join a caravan of gypsies. When I played it for the first time, I thought I was doing well until I had to do some mission where you had to patrol and kill numerous Skaven early on. I learned that I was bad at tactics. So I had to get good.I got good... or so I thought. Then I got mauled by an orc riding a wyvern or something. It was terrifying, as I was a dumb tween when I first played this game.Many years later I came back to it and eventually beat it, even after numerous deaths. I still wish I had the half of the instruction manual that included the psychology section though.Anyway, I wrote about Shadow of the Horned Rat because this game brings back memories of my training montage of getting good at Warhammer.This GameI first heard ofMordheim: City of the Damnedwhen I subscribed to Sheepdog Gaming on the Youtube sometime after I got into Blood Bowl 2. I saw a video about a Skaven warband, and immediately I had to watch it. I learned that Mordheim was a strategy-based game with permadeath and various other things. I decided to watch a bit more of various people playing Mordheim to get an idea of whether I wanted this game or not. Eventually I decided that I'd get it and start off as the Skaven, because I find them hilarious compared to the other factions. I eventually started at least one warband from each faction (as of this edit, there are five in total).I had to turn my settings to the lowest that I possibly could, because my PC is rather bad for gaming and I need to upgrade both my computer and my internet connection at some point in the future. Regardless of this, I can tell that the game is good looking, even if my settings make it so that my human captain has no pupils (he also went amok after getting pounded by cultists, so I could consider that a side effect of him being mentally deranged). I can also tell from seeing other reviews and noting Youtubers saying so that the loading times are pretty long regardless of my computer's performance. Hopefully this patch helps a little with this. (A patch helped with this somewhat.)Anyway, the RNG of this game does get to me sometimes, but I'm very much used to the punishment as a result of my aforementioned experience with Shadow of the Horned Rat. I've had some good RNG too, thankfully, such as being able to end certain Marked for Death battles fairly quickly with the bonus objective completed or having a metric ton of wyrdstone at a good place to screw with the AI.I have no input regarding multiplayer, as I'm afraid of losing my internet connection while playing it. I'll update this when or if I can get some experience in.Regarding gameplay, it's a pretty solid strategy game. The AI can be rather dumb sometimes, but challenges happen just as much as dumb AI activity happens for me, so I can't complain too much. There have only been a couple of occasions where the AI got stuck on corners for me, although I have also had a couple times where the AI cannot decide whether it wants to jump down or climb up a ledge, and will do so back and forth until the unit moves within ambush range of my deranged captain who wants an excuse to not flee from combat. Anyways, the AI could be worse, but it could also be better.Rating:For me, I give this game a whip designed for self-flagellation arranged in the form of an 8 out of 10. Well, it'd look more like a B, but close enough.For a general audience, I give this game a whip designed for self-flagellation arranged in a 7 out of 10. The punishment of the RNG stings a fair bit, but you feel absolved once you manage your RNG, achieve victory, and dominate your foes through clever tactics. If you're into Warhammer, strategy, and challenge, pick up this game. It is possible that the challenge may not be the sort you're looking for, so this is rated a 7 instead of an 8 for that reason."
