,Recommended,276810,24627950,"Posted: 30 July, 2016",all,Emmys,"This is a really fun adaptation of Mordheim.I've been a big fan of games like this and Inquisitor for quite a long time in table-top land, and I love the Warhammer universes. However, I will do my best to not be biased here in the hopes of helping you decide if this game is for you or not!To begin, this game is tough as nails, and can be even tougher depending which warband you pick and how you set up your team. Much like tabletop Mordheim, your future success largely in part depends on how well you do in the first few missions. If you do well, rack up lots of stuff to sell and Wyrdstone, all while hardly getting anyone injured, you should get to the part where the game becomes more manageable, even if you make a mistake and fail a mission horribly. Let me say this loud and clearly though, for every new person in the room:Melee. Trumps. Range.Yeah, you heard me. In this game, you will suffer many, many to-hit penalities. You will set up overwatch shots just slightly at the wrong angle and watch helplessly as your archer gets smashed in one round. This is a game about gangs, and what do gangs do to get the advantage? They GANG UP on a smaller number of units, normally in melee, in this case, and they pound them into the dirt. In table-top, you want to swarm enemy models and roll as many dice as possible. Missing is guaranteed, hits are god-sends, and it's the same formula here. Mostly melee (of all varities - don't be that person who goes all swords/shields and then finds themselves losing because dual-wielding rats are stabbing you in the back,) with a few good ranged units. To put it into perspective, I start like this: I immediately go to the market and see if I can buy a decent ranged weapon for my warband leader. Bow/etc is -okay-, dueling pistols/warlock pistols are what you want, though. I then slap those on my hero's alternate equipment, recruit ONE archer henchman if available (not a special character - I strongly suggest taking the melee special character first,) and then fill up on melee.Next up, optimize your weapons. Bonuses to hit, bonuses to ambush damage, parry chance, etc - all great. Heavy weapons? Best used on characters who hit well on their own. Armor is also not always the best choice for every character either. Sometimes taking that 50% dodge is the best choice you can get, and the cheapest, too.If you try the above, and play carefully (be sure to give your archer two daggers or something in their offhand, too. Archers I tend to give armor asap as well,) you should be gravy. With those first 3-4 missions done, you'll be feeling good.I bet you'll even feel great.But then?The first story mission happens.And you're in for a whole new level of hell.Don't even click on that mission until your rating is closer to what it says the enemy has. You can see this by clicking on but not accepting the mission. It will destroy your life, your warbands life, and♥♥♥♥♥♥your pockets. It really will, especially a particular few races (RNG can be really rough on the humans for that first mission. Believe me.)Graphics are decent, controls take adjusting to (your first warband is doomed to death if you're like me and mess up the controls for a bit before getting used to them,) and sometimes you will get grumpy that so-and-so enemy just charged through a narrow crack between three ambushing characters.But hey, welcome to Mordheim. It's all about luck and tenacity and a whole lot of death. Do suggest, 8.5/10, needs more races with cheaper DLC (the current price model is 'meh.')Multiplayer suggested over everything else, even if you do the one where no changes happen to your warband, but thanks to the RNG and the computer's tendency to stick to the 'gang up and pound you' strategy, even playing vs the computer can be fun."
76561198002554370,Recommended,276810,30378483,Posted: 7 March,all,Scary Terry,"This is, at least for me, exactly what I'm looking for in a Games Workshop game. Turn based strategy, cool level progression, lots of customization. It's close to the table top games people love. All the warbands have their own stregnths and weaknesses. I only wish there were more warbands to choose from. With the endless font of crap GW vomits up this one stands out as a gem. I'm very looking forward to Necromunda, hopefully they keep the things that make this game great.This game is quite difficult, so I only recommend it if you enjoy a challenge. Expect your first couple warbands to join the corpses strewn about the Mordeheim landscape, but the first time you actually reach endgame will feel like a huge accomplishment.Many people complain about the game feeling unfair, their guys missing repeatedly with an 80% chance to hit. However 80% isnt 100 and you will hit about 8 out of 10 times. Its all about positioning, using your tanks to block and hold units while you surround and destroy others with your damage classes. The only thing that seems kind of weak to me is the magic, you're better off equipping your mages with 2 handed weapons and actually doing damage... but then I was never much of a magic player, maybe someone else figured out how to make the most of it.Highly recommend this game. Its atmospheric and immersive, and you actually come to love your units. I recommend giving them all unique names and backstory to enhance your gaming experience. Please GW, more of this, stick with this developer, we would love it if you put out more high quality games like Mordeheim than the endless stream of garbage we have been getting.For those of you having trouble, a couple tips. Keep your warband together. Don't even take missions that split your warband up (particularly the ones that split you into 3 small groups) Make sure to keep your lighter damage units behind your heavy tanks, resist the urge to use their faster movement to take them out front. When you set up ambushes make sure that they don't end up pinching the enemy in a doorway where you can't surround them. Impressive units can be a real problem if they wind up in the middle of your warband where they can create absolute havoc. Try to use the alleys and doorways to trap enemy impressives, as the AI won't be able to get them unstuck. Above all never engage anyone alone, especially with your leader and heroes. They are too valuable to risk, disengage and run to your minions who are expendable. Don't spend money on the minons until late game, if some of your units have to die, better them than your Bosses and heroes.You really have to invest some time to make your warband great. Don't give up after an hour or two of playing the game, and really try to go for the extra objectives, as getting them will make your levels spring forward."
