76561198088047098,Not Recommended,276810,21154137,"Posted: 12 February, 2016",all,Noxys,"I can't even begin to describe how frustrating this game is.  The worst part about it is that I like this style of game, and I desperately want to like this one, but I just can't because it's not honest.  The roll system in this game indicates a percentage likelihood to succeed in any given task, so when I have 7 people who all have a greater than 75% chance to hit their targets and I hit twice in 3 rounds, I have a problem.  If this was one scenario then I'd write it off as a set of bad rolls, but it's not just one scenario.  As the Skaven, who have the best agility, I failed 7 out of 8 of the agility tests I tried with over 70% chance to succeed.  As the mercenaries who have the best ballistics skills starting out, I never hit once with a ranged weapon.  The Sisters of Sigmar were the group I had the best luck with and I did that by tanking and trading blows, but that only works when you can actually hit at the rate you're supposed to.  So take any given % chance they show you and subtract somewhere between 20 and 50 from it and you'll have the actual rate of success.  If the numbers were accurate I'd love this game.  Instead I hate it because I'm constantly expecting what it tells me.Edit:  I've forced myself to continue playing in order to get my money's worth, and while I still don't recommend the game, I do have some more insight into it now.  I'm leaving my initial review because most of what was said still stands and it accurately portrays the frustration I felt upon initially starting the game.  I've since found that the game seriously suffers from an inverse difficulty curve where the game is extremely difficult for people who haven't put any time into it yet.  The more you play the more bonuses you get for both existing and new warbands.  This means that warbands you start later will have fewer starting problems, mostly that they won't feel forced to take missions that feel outside of their level.  The issues with rng still exist at higher levels.  When I have a skill that initally has a 75% chance to succeed and I cast it 3 times at base and 2 times with a plus 15% chance to succeed and I only get one success and 3 ""divine wrath"" results that basically end that characters turn (and the divine wrath chance was only 15% chance on each cast) I feel as though instead of being told my success rate I'm being told my failure rate.  I understand that the game is supposed to be difficult, but there is definitely something wrong with the rng.  I'm even contemplating keeping track of everything I do to see just how far off the percentages are.  The game can become enjoyable, if still frustrating, but it just takes too much effort to really be worth it in my opinion."
76561198013645324,Not Recommended,276810,25182441,"Posted: 27 August, 2016",all,tom2782,"As a fan of Games Workshop I was looking forward to playing this game.  Positives first it looks great, has not lagged, crashed or frozen on me once.  Sounds great and does a dame good job is emulating the table top game it is based on.  The reasons why I am not recommending this game boil down to the combat.  To be fair to Rogue Factor they have done a good job in merging the rolls to hit, wound and save into one single action but however there are some major problems.First the percentage chance show when about to hit an opponent is just wrong.  It only shows your chance of hitting after your characters modifiers are taken into account, but not the enemies.  The community keeps pointing out that the opponent’s modifiers are shown; they are just not included in the calculations for hitting.  This is especially frustrating when despite being told you have a 95% chance to hit, you miss four times in a row.  Second and perhaps the biggest the range for the RNG used in this game is too high.  When turning a table top game that requires dice to play into a computer game using an RNG is a good way of measuring the dice rolls.  In this case however Rogue Factor have taken a game that uses dice numbered between 1-6 and ups it to 1-100.  This is a major issue as it greatly increases the chances of missing and failing to repel attacks.  The worst one of these I experienced was having a single Novice from the Sisters of Sigmar kill two of my henchmen and my war band leader on her own because I could not roll a single hit.I would suggest you play Bloodbowl instead as Cyanide has done a far better job at converting a tabletop game into a computer game."
