76561198013684741,Recommended,276810,19212224,"Posted: 22 November, 2015",all,Jaketh Shae,"Mordheim is a turn based strategy game with some vague similarities to the XCOM series but set in the dark, gritty fantasy world of Games Workshop's Warhammer Fantasy setting.This game is an adaption of the classic tabletop game Mordheim (which was itself the fantasy reskin of the excellent TT game Necromunda) and it captures the setting extremely well. The graphics and music evoke the right atmosphere and look damn good, especially when you realise what a small team it was working on this game.The game itself is hard. Like, really hard. Particualrly at the beginning, where the learning curve is like an overhanging cliff (and the wide skill selection is an avalanche that starts when you're part way up). The tutorials are good but they don't cover everything, they're definitely worth going through though. It does get easier and you'll find that you're able to do Brutal and Deadly missions and generally win, although that doesn't mean you won't lose people to going Out of Action during those wins.Ah yes, out of action... This game has permanent consequences for your actions. There's no save scumming, although there is an ironman style autosave feature in case of crashes, etc. Other than that you have to live with your decsisions and, due to it's TT roots, the roll of the die. Yeah, sometimes RNG can screw you, it's just that sort of game. Your mooks will go down and out and, when they do, they will end up picking up injuries or straight up dying. That part of Mordheim and, at least for me, part of the fun!So the purpose of the game? You've been sent to Mordheim by a baacker who is funding your activities in the city. Their exact nature and reasons for sending you there vary from faction to faction but suiffice it to say you work for them. And what you're doing for them is collecting warpstone, a resource that's scattered throughout the maps. You will periodically have deliveries to fill for them where they require a particualr amount of warpstone. Failing to make those deliveries will eventually lose you the game so try to make them on time. Other than that you will be levelling up your warriors and your warband, as well as you as a player via the Veteran System whereby you get perks like additional starting gold and access to Veteran Skills. Your warband will gain stat increases, more strategy points and offence points, as well as gaining skill points to spend on the bewildering array of passive and active skills available (warning: they aren't cheap, especially when you master a skill). Some of your guys will gain access to spells, and as you level up new hero types (and eventually the mighty Impressives) will be come available to your warband.  You'll also loot more powerful equipment and begin discover magical formulae that allow you to place marks on your weapons and armour, that do a variety of things.All in all I would definitely recommend the game. I very much enjoy it and can't wait to have a try at multiplayer (I've only done single player thus far), where I think the game will really shine. Just be aware that it is a hardcore exsperience. You will lose matches, you will have people get injured and die, your equipment will be looted from their bodies, you will struggle for gold to pay your warband and buy skills and replacement warriors. That's an integral part of Mordheim and might mean that the game isn't for you, which is fine. It is for me though, I absolutely love it!"
