76561197971089934,Recommended,276810,19281083,"Posted: 25 November, 2015",all,*A-B* *StAtiC*9*,"As an old-timey player of the table-top version of this game, I have to say that this is the most complete and in depth video game iteration of any of Games Workshop's properties to date. Nearly everything that existed in the skirmish level miniatures game is here; and I can't get enough of it. From unit custimization, down to the weapons, armor, skills, and appearances, to the tough-as-nails, ""please don't let my veteran die"" urgency is represented here. Further, the ability to take your battle hardened crew online to scrap with your friends or other players across the world was not only a necessity, but a welcome addition to an already excellent game. If turn-based strategy is your bread and butter, or even just your soup de jour, Mordheim should have you coming back for more! Old school X-Com fans should buy this game without reservation. A+"
76561197990013217,Recommended,276810,19358318,"Posted: 29 November, 2015",all,Captain Datsun,"The best multiplayer tactical turn-based strategy game I've ever encountered, bar none. As a lifelong devotee to the turn-based classics like XCOM, Jagged Alliance and Silent Storm, I've always wanted the beauty of Necromunda's consequence-laden multiplayer skirmishes brought to the PC - and this game delivers.After two days of owning the title, I've accumulated 17 hours of multiplayer-only battles, and the matches I now have under my belt are without doubt the most memorable strategy gaming experiences I've ever had - even better than playing Necromunda with miniatures. Hell, I'm terrified this game will distract me from my own programming work!As everybody will tell you, the third-person movement and control scheme will seem strange at first, but they serve to immerse you more; like how Firaxis' introduction of cinematic shots for dramatic moments did, but better. Warband management is the real-deal Necromunda/Mordheim experience; defeats and victories don't feel so black and white, as even a victor might walk away worse for wear, or - as is the case against a friend - economically poorer for not focusing on resources.This is the first time I've ever felt compelled to write a review for a game, but as somebody who's been trying for years to find a multiplayer strategy experience that captures the nuances of the Necromunda/Mordheim systems, and as somebody who's programming a TBS myself, I desperately want this developer to succeed with this product and consider releasing a DLC for some of the fringe-factions.I implore you to buy it, harass your friends to buy it, and start a small tourney where each of you has a warband that you only pit against each other in multiplayer. You'll have more fun than any other TBS game can offer you right now, at least in the multiplayer aspect."
