,Recommended,276810,28794360,"Posted: 29 December, 2016",all,Klozkoth,"So there are a few things to say about Mordheim. It's a very challenging game for starters. I will say right off the bat to do the tutorials. At least the combat ones. I think I'm decent at X-COM, heard this was similar, and thought those skills would transfer. Hoo was I wrong. If you go in expecting a ""Fantasy X-COM"" you'll be in for a rude awakening. It's one of the more comparable games out there, but there are still plenty of differences.The focus is very much on melee in Mordheim. There are ranged units, but pretty much every unit you have will be in melee at some point in their life. The RNG is also much closer to ""random"". I've had units miss 95% shots/attacks before, but I've seen the AI get just as unlucky. There doesn't seem to be a boost to the rolls for either side from what I can tell. The randomness extends to the injury rolls after combat as well. When a unit is defeated during the mission it isn't instant death luckily. After the mission is over those units roll on the injury table. They can roll a decent variety of injuries, such as missing arms, legs, eye, mental damage, or death. They can also end up fine or with minor injuries, so you aren't guaranteed to have crippled troops, at least not initially.There is also much less story than I thought there would be. I enjoy the character and warband building/personalization of the game enough to not mind a lack of story. Something to keep in mind if you expect an epic tale, or even a story that further dives into why you're there, how it affects the area or world, etc. The meat of the game is in doing missions to gather resources and level up. Nothing super exciting, but I find the gameplay and warband building enjoyable enough to make up for it.My favorite aspect of warband building is just how much you can go into it. Each unit has levels, your warband has levels, and you yourself have levels through the veteran system. The veteran system is one of the ways each successive warband you create gets stronger. As you accomplish tasks you'll gain veteran xp. Gain enough and it will increase your veteran rank which gives you a skill point, as well as benefits to buying/selling, and benefits when you create a new warband.In all I recommend Mordheim to anyone that enjoys tactical games that are truly challenging, as well as anyone that enjoys the Warhammer setting. If you enjoy both, then you should already own this!"
