76561197985776801,Recommended,276810,20782122,"Posted: 27 January, 2016",all,Apoc,"This game is very good if you're not afraid to lose a few characters here and there. especially on your first playthrough.People whine about the Random Number Generator because they missed a few hits in desperate situations, but my guess is they skipped statistics classes in college, and they shouldn't have put their characters in a desperate situation in the first place.If you flip a coin five times and it lands on heads five time, you're not gonna claim you've solved the coin flipping rule of the universe.Sometimes, in Mordheim COTD, you need to shackle the opponent's impressive character, but somehow your 95% succes chance Magister fails and gets stunned in front of everyone, and your poor sod facing the impressive character will have a bad time.Sometimes though, you play tight and get a lucky crit on their most dangerous character, and turn a uneasy battle into a piece of cake.You never hear people whine about lucky crits, though.You could see this game as an XCOM set in the Warhammer world with a default hard difficulty (which isn't that hard once you get the hang of it).Some of your characters will die, and that's ok, learn to manage a rooster big enough to handle those situations.If you want a blissful experience without any character dying, stick to the first xcom reboot on easy difficulty.Mordheim: COTD is beautiful, challenging and fun."
