76561198048058172,Recommended,276810,30296706,Posted: 3 March,all,msj1117,"Excellent, hard, and honest turn-based strategy game in the vein of XCOM, etc. You take a warband of character classes into a spooky city and engage other warbands. The game allows for wonderful customization of your characters' stats and you can design a particular warband memberjust so.Then that warband member gets annihilated in combat and needs his leg amputated and you have to rethink your build for him because he can't climb walls anymore.It's an Ironman-mode only game, so there's no coming back from a maneuver, decision, or result. If you aren't thinking about strategy your warband can get wiped easily by the AI, suffer permanent injuries, and you're back to square one and need to hire a few new characters. Do you risk going for loot or a gem and exposing a character to a potential ambush, or do you hide for one round so a few other characters can catch up and add security against a potential engagement? Decisions like that happen on practically every turn, and they add incredible atmosphere to the combat.It's procedural, so every non-story mission is unique and the replayability is fantastic.A hard game at first but you eventually get the hang of things and learn to be patient and thinkcarefullybefore you act.There is a nice selection of guides written by members of the community that I found invaluable. They cover things like warband management, combat tips, levelling, which skills to train for X builds, etc., and make many aspects of the game much more approchable for new players."
,Not Recommended,276810,30480088,Posted: 12 March,all,Greenwhite79,"Unforgiving and repetitive… but also challenging & nerdy!So in this black or white system from steam there’s just thumbs up or down. The question is: Would you recommend this game to others? The answer to this question is… NO!Why?This is not a mainstream game like XCOM, HOMM & Co. It’s a hardcore Warhammer niche game for freaks & nerds! So if you consider yourself more of a mainstream player, then this game is most likely not for you. The /ragequit chance is probably over 95%... (There’s actually an achievement for it.)If you want to test the waters for turnbased RPG & strategy RNG games, I strongly recommend to get XCOM first (It’s easier and better in most aspects than Mordheim & I enjoyed it tremendously). Put it on Classic & Ironman mode to see how it goes. If you enjoy this kind of gameplay & want more of it, get XCom 2. If you done with that, there is nothing else on your plate & you get Mordheim in a Steam-Sale, then go for it and try it out.I have some likes and dislikes about the game.1st  dislike: You can’t start at once. You have to go through boring tutorials and then watch guide videos and read guides online. You have to carefully plan your Warband (party progression) and execute everything by the book or else you’re most likely not gonna make it.2nd dislike: It contains several of my personal game design No Go’s:-	Dead Ends -> Did I mention that you’re most likely not gonna make it?-	Missing difficulty settings -> Sucks… /ragequit… / You’re most likely not gonna make it…-	Unlimited spawning of enemies -> In story-mission, which are optional & can be ignored-	Limiting the savegame options (fixed savepoints or online-only savegame) - As a PC player I want a free savegame-system -> If you manage to get your sgame broken it’s… Game Over!-	Repetitive MOTS gameplay & mindless grinding -> There is not enough content to keep you entertained for long, maps, enemies, loot, names => everything repeats itself after a few hours.-	Missing space for exploration and experimenting -> The game is about perfection and extremely unforgiving-	Absence of logic -> Mission ends when the enemy flees or gets killed… What do you do now? Right, you loot the map or auto-collect the rest of the loot like in XCom… But no, not in Mordheim, you only get a small fracture of the uncollected loot, so all you just did in this mission was practically for nothing… As the AI normally attacks you in the 2nd or 3rd round, you’ll have a very small window to explore freely.It’s also very hard to fulfill optional sidequests, for example you need to collect stuff from certain enemies. This is very hard due to the early routing of enemy warbands. After 3 from 7 or 4 from 9 are killed they rout and the mission ends immediately – especially frustrating if just beat down the one you needed and this ends the mission before you can loot. In this cases the game should marked the sidequest as fulfilled. I mean think this through: You get the order bring the trinket of a certain enemy home, you beat him down and his homies run away and you leave the area without the trinket… yeah, right…-	Unhelpful & boring tutorials-	Cheating AI (in general, not sure if the AI cheats in the game…)Likes:+ solid engine, great core game play, rogue-like ‘challenge factor’, nice graphics, no critical bugs+ Game has it’s moment, e.g. when you’re hiding behind a door in Ambush Mode, the enemy walks through it and you instantly kill the unit with a critical hit… Muahahah… - Pretty rare though…+ Crazy stuff like this seems to happen (Cult of the possed):Mnezocles 19 Dec, 2016 @ 8:58amGot severed arm on a mutant. Next rank had a mutation, grew it right back."
