,Recommended,276810,26220779,"Posted: 25 October, 2016",all,Brascus,"I had previously written a review for this when it was in Early Access.  Now that it is in full release I figured I'd better get with the program.Mordheim is a turn-based strategy game based on the Game Workshop Mordheim setting.  Four different warbands (six if you get the DLC) square off against one another in a ruined city, competing for control of the city and the resources it contains.  It is difficult, unforgiving, and I love every second of it.One of the things that stands out most to me is the way the gameplay functions.  When a unit takes their turn, instead of relying on any sort of grid, they are free to move around in a third person free roaming mode, limited to their movement range.  This gives the game a very open and exploratory feel, and really feels like a skirmish instead of a board game with pretty graphics.Each army is unique and favors different playstyles.  They have their own unique skills, equipment, stat limitations, and unit types.  This provides a huge range of options with which to customize your playstyle.  On that subject you'd better get good at the playstyle as well, because the game will punish you if you don't.One of the core principles of this game is that choices matter.  If one of your units falls in battle, they may suffer injuries that will affect their stats, lose equipment, or even die and have to be replaced.  If you do well, they will be rewarded with experience points that level their stats, provide skill points, and increase their health.The PVP is a solid experience, though sometimes bugs get in the way.  Occasionally there will be issues causing you and your opponents games to ""desync,"" causing different outcomes for checks.  This could mean that sometimes a unit falls out of action for you, but not your opponent.  It's a problem.  Most of the time though it works just fine, and battles against a skilled opponent are still very rewarding.  It works well enough, that I've done some one off games on my YouTube channel, and even joined six other YouTubers and participated in a PVP league that ran for at least 16 battles.  My point here is don't let the occasional bug scare you off.Another benefit to this game is the DLC.  Since release they have added two additional factions.  The Witch Hunters, and the Undead provide very different styles of play from the other four, and I still don't feel like any faction inherently rises above all the others.  In addition to this, they added a Hired Swords DLC that added another four units to the game that can be usable by the original factions.  This includes the Poison Wind Globadier, Smuggler, Worf Priest of Ulric, and the Doomsayer.  The Globadier and Doomsayer can be hired by the chaotic aligned factions while the Wolf Priest, and Smuggler are hired by the order factions.  It's a great way to mix up your war band and through an unexpected wrench at your opponent.All said and done I would highly recommend this game.  The great support from the development team, the wonderful art style and game features, and the originality in the maps and warbands combines to make a very memorable and enjoyable experience."
