76561198019163801,Recommended,276810,19660968,"Posted: 12 December, 2015",all,Tochimo,"Mordheim: City of the DamnedI’ve always loved table top games and played a little Warhammer 40k back in the day, and I’m a huge fan of 40k themed games, but I never really got into the classic Warhammer setting.  This was my first real experience both with the classic Warhammer setting and Mordheim, and I love it.The gameplay feels like how a tabletop conversion with great graphics should, and at first there isn’t a whole lot to fights – knock them out before they knock you out.  As the game picks up you gain levels, new units, items, skills, and enchantments and things start taking off.  Skills and items sets, along with unit placement and scavenging, becomes a huge part of every encounter.  If you get far enough, you can even unlock some units from another faction for more diversity and options.As many people have discussed, the game is brutally unforgiving.  Think XCOM on Ironman and one of the hardest settings – as much as I wish I had the option to turn off “Ironman” in this game, it’s built in.  The Random Number Generator (RNG) is more forgiving than it used to be, but people who are “perfectionists” will quickly find themselves stressed at all the things they cannot control.  You will miss with a 95% chance to hit, either because you rolled a “1” or because they dodged.  You will also get hit when your guy has “135%” chance to dodge incoming attacks.  And that’s the beauty of a true table top conversion.  Even gods have brain farts.The weakest aspects of the game, at this point, is balancing and AI – and they Venn diagram into one another where the weakness of the game is concerned (for me, at least).  While each faction does something a little better than the other, the units are mostly the same across the board with the only real exception being Impressives and the Chaos faction’s large number of Fear/Terror/Alone immunities.  The AI also leaves something to be desired.  I often find that 1 or 2 of the enemies in a fight get stuck on walls, in doorways, or on stairs – especially common for the larger Ogre, Rat Ogre, and Chaos Spawn Impressives.  This is great for the player because it means less to manage, but it is also frustrating – it makes victories feel cheap, keeps you from fulfilling optional bounty objectives (as it is often the bounty targets who get stuck!), and you never know when that guy is going to decide to stop derping into a wall and join the fight.  Another problem is the way the AI will often bee-line for you - which means that Heroes, Leaders, and Impressives (that don’t get stuck) are the first you run into, which also means they’re the first of the enemies to go down before the henchman can support them if you’re patient and set up proper ambush points.  The way the game “balances” the poor AI decision making and pathing is by simply making them stronger than you.  In a “normal” fight, the easiest on the map, enemies have more wounds (hit points) and hit harder.  It scales up with difficulty; the hardest missions simply have units with 40% more wounds and damage on top of their guys having more skills and better stats.  What this means is that you will never have an even match-up against the AI; you’re always expected to out play them as you’re never on equal terms.Despite the issues above, the developers are intent on polishing their game.  They are already working on improving the AI and making other adjustments as/when the community brings up issues.  The game has a lot of potential for growth as the Warhammer world is huge, with tons of units and factions that could be included, as well as more cosmetic options for people who are really into the customization aspect.  I look forward to seeing what the developers do and I hope to see more games like this, especially a Warhammer 40k type!"
