76561198006644483,Recommended,276810,34371895,Posted: 20 August,all,commonwomble,"To all intents and purposes, this is Darkest Dungeon in 3D, with all that entails. It looks good, the environments are interesting and detailed, and the atmosphere is delightfully dark, with some wicked humour lurking beneath the surface. Warband building and customisation is extensive, with new options and toys being drip-fed to you at precisely the right rate - you are rarely overwhelmed with options, and there are always new toys you can get after 'just one more game'.On the negative side, the UI and controls can be fiddly, the AI can occasionally be a bit daft (although hardly a game-breaker), and like DD, you have to watch out for RNGesus - If he is against you, you'll suffer. That said, even these defeats add character to the game - My Vampire lord lost an arm on his third outing and I couldn't afford to replace him at that point. So I rebuilt him as a dodge-tank instead, and now Wilhelm the One-Armed Vampire is the terror of the Merchant Quarter!If I had one major complaint, it would be the warband story missions - some are very good, but others are a brutal, unforgiving slog. (Looking at you, library missions).At heart, this is an interactive board-game. Bear that in mind, and it's easy to overlook it's faults and have a blast leading your merry band of murderous miscreants through the City of the Damned.(Although I do have to make a complaint about false advertising - to the uninitiated, the screenshots might suggest there are Skaven in this game. Everyone knows that there is no such thing of course, and anyone who says otherwise is a vile heretic!) See you on the streets!"
