,Not Recommended,276810,20795328,"Posted: 27 January, 2016",all,gaynorvader,"PROS:Beautiful AestheticPolished GraphicsNice settingHUGE skilltreeCONS:VERY long loading times.Terrible looting system.Very shallow warband customisationSuperficial tacticsPoor TutorialsNo clear rulesNo terrain bonuses/penaltiesI've never played Mordheim the tabletop game, but I heard it was good. This isn't. All the nice looking set pieces and good voice acting can't save what is a very shallow turn based tactics game. Most TBS have some kind of tactics to them, certain troops being suited towards certain roles or certain weapons being good against some and weak against others. This game has none of that. Aside from being able to see further from higher up (I think) and being able to ambush around corners, there might as well be no terrain. Ranged characters seem like they'd be good as long as you protected them, but they only get 1 attack compared to the 2-3 a melee character gets. At first it seemed like you'd be able to set up little traps and things, but the AI is so brain dead it's better to just group your warband together and gang up on the enemy one at a time. The tutorials make a meal of explaining the simplest of concepts and indulge in large blocks of text for small amounts of information. It's never clear what characters can equip what until you try to equip it. I thought my captain would be allowed to equip a pistol for instance, nope. Why? No clue. Captains aren't capable of holding them I guess. Maybe there's a skill I can get or something, but it'd have been nice to know in advance.The real let down is the lack of diversity in the warbands, maybe it imporves later, but to begin with you get your leader (always the same one), you can hire a hero (1 of 3 choices, you only have 1 choice to start with) and 3 henchemen (2 different kinds, ranged and not ranged). Leter on you unlock more slots including an ""impressive"" (basically a big guy for any bloodbowl fans) slot, there is 1 ""impressive"" choice for each race. You can use the skills to diversify the warband a bit and make more unique characters, but then if one dies, you have to go back to genericland and pick one of the faceless drones to take his place.I was left with a pretty lame experience of Mordheim, and there are some who'll say I didn't give it a fair chance, but I want my refund, I don't want to be stuck hoping the game ""might get good eventually"". Glancing over the positive reviews makes me think you perhaps need to already love the tabletop game for this game to be worth getting."
