,Not Recommended,276810,21668798,"Posted: 6 March, 2016",all,Roameo,"Pros:Faithfully replicates a lot of the Mordheim wargaming experienceCons:Faithfully replicates a lot of the Mordheim wargaming experienceJokes aside, I really wanted to like this game. I'm a big fan of Warhammer in general, so anything in that setting deserves a look in my book. This game fails to deliver on quality, tho, and I'm a bit salty that I spent cash on it at this point. I kept playing, hoping it would ""loosen up"" and get better as I learned the systems more, but that didn't happen.I played Mercenaries, so your experience may vary depending on your warband preference.Main problemThe main problem this game has is usability. Information I crave isn't provided when I desire it. For example when an enemy is in ambush stance, and I see them, why can I not see how far their ambush range extends? This is vital information for planning my approach, but the information isn't there! This problem is confounded by the fact that ambush ranges vary depending on the movement range of the unit doing the ambush, so you can't learn an approximate distance through experience either.The same applies to traps of all kinds. When I have perceived a trap to be there, why can I not see the trigger area? For a game that wants to be tactical, it makes it very hard to make tactical decisions.The game would be a lot more rewarding if it gave me enough information.Outside a certain distance from my active unit, I can't see traversal-nodes anymore (leap, jump down, etc.) This is tactically important information, but I have to awkwardly run my unit closer just to see this info. Bogs down the game with unnecessary busywork.Secondary problemAdding to the usability problems is the fact that units block a larger area around them than their model indicates. This fact interplays with the level design, which is rife with small corridors, walkways, stairs and bridges to make it a horrible experience trying to maneuver your units around.If you get an archer out on a walkway, you can't be certain you'll be able to funnel any other units past him even though it visually looks completely possible. It's extremely frustrating when your entire plan of attack is foiled by visual misinformation like that. After being hurt by this issue a few times, I started playing extremely conservatively. This bogs down the entire game, as you can't assume based on visual clues what's possible, and have to take the safe bet at every juncture.OtherThe game soaks in randomness. Sure, Mordheim the wargame does, too, but the encounter layouts that aim to provide variation are frightening because of it. When there's a large probability of my units permanently dying, it'sinfuriatingwhen one is dropped in the middle of three Sisters of Sigmar that proceed to bash him to death in unison with no recourse possible. I have no control over this. If I was given the chance to stack up my forces in a manner I wanted, I could at least take the blame for the misstep myself.The strategy/offense point system feels sub-par. Moving a huge distance and not moving at all has no bearing on how many attacks the unit gets to do. This feels awkward, and makes strategy points less valuable once engaged in melee.Please create a way to revert any movements made on a unit to the starting to position.This is unnecessarily awkward, as I have to retrace my steps to get back the strategy points used. Sometimes, moving in a certain way around corners and through doors will make it impossible to retrace my steps, too."
