76561198023159593,Recommended,276810,20150420,"Posted: 31 December, 2015",all,Stormtyrant,"TL,DRPros]/b]Visually the world looks good.Captures the style of the classic Mordheim table top game and adds to it.The warbands carrysomeof their flavor from the original game well.Combat is simple and easy to learn early on, but can be expanded on with skills.The maps are great and intuitive. They are both easy and difficult to navigate at the same time.Unlike most Turn based games your moves aren't locked in.Room to grow. Theres plenty of source material to develop more warbands and hopefully a better story mode.ConsRNG in this game is almost too painful.The maps could be more diverse.The warbands only carry a very limited amount of their inspiration over from the table top. leading to ...The warbands are too similar.Very low amount of customization.Lack of a regular Story to play.RNGI truly do like this game so far. It has a lot to offer, to anyone who enjoys turn based strategy (TBS) games and/or Gamesworkshop. The warband all fit their flavors aestheticly. There is RPG elements mixed into the characters; It is deceptively deep if you can keep your characters alive long enough. But thats not to say this game doesnt have it's downfalls. Repetitive maps generic feeling warbands and rage-inducing RNG all scream for some serious future updates. Here I will cover some of the pros and cons I encountered along the way.P6) The most refreshing part of the TBS side of the game is the ability to move your character throughout the world and then back to explore a different avenue, before coming to the point that you want to stop. Being able to freely explore the buildings and streets is a HUGE boon. P5) There are traps and enemies along the way that can stop your exploration though. The maps are built like city streets and inner city mansions, making them easy to navigate. The catch is all the traps along the way that will stop your movement along the way. Also, many of the buildings are in ruins so you might enter one side hoping to cut through to find that the other side is blocked off. C2) After playing for awhile however, the maps start feeling too similar the buildings all the same. It's like if you were walking through a forest. ""Sure, this clearing is different than the last. But it's still really similar.""Being a longtime Gamesworkshop fan since WH40k: Chaos Gate and an avid player of the Mordheim table top game, I was really looking forward to this game. Getting into the game the aesthetics were spot-on. Dark gritty dirty broken. Exactly what longtime fans expect. The look and feel of the warbands is also on point. Where it fails is customization. You can change a few bits of clothing here and there. You can have some different colors but nothing more. That limited customization bleeds over into the gameplay of the warband themselves. Each warband plays in a very similar manner. You have x ammount of little dudes with x amount of heroes. Each warband has the same numbers. Each warband can use most of the same weapons. The flavors of the original game are there for all the warbands except skaven. Chaos guys mutate. Sisters gals are vendictive nuns with divine magic. Merc are well Mercs but they have access to the largest array of wepapons. Skaven are supposed to be an endless horde of assassin rat-men. Because the limited number of henchmen they are not endless. Skaven barely hold onto the idea of being assassins by having a few poison skills.More to come later im tired time for bed"
