76561198007859795,Not Recommended,276810,21618904,"Posted: 4 March, 2016",all,Flix,"I made my mind up to give this a negative review pretty early in playing, but thought I'd give it a bit of an extra chance. Unfortunately, it's not really improved a great deal.I've played a lot of the Games Workshop games and I've enjoyed the vast majority of them. I liked the idea of Mordheim as something which has more of an inherent story built in as your warband develops and takes on progressively harder missions (unlike e.g. Dawn of War I which had very little natural storyline and Dawn of War II which moved away a fair bit from Warhammer 40,000). Unfortunately I felt they missed the opportunity to put in some sort of story campaign, or at least a heavier story element in to the pick your own adventure style campaign that is included.I'm not a huge fan of hardcore games (i.e. no saving and going back), but I appreciate that this is a conscious design decision by the makers. However, I feel that combining that hardcore element with a very steep learning curve decreases the chance that you'll actually keep playing long enough to hit an enjoyable point. I found myself repeatedly restarting as my warband increasingly reached the point where I couldn't do anything (e.g. everyone injured and no gold left). Perhaps it reaches a cruising point later on, but I've still never hit that and I feel like I've given it a fair crack.The warband tutorial is very dry and basically just gives you a slideshow of what all the buttons do. It doesn't give you worked examples which means you either have to remember it all, keep going back to the tutorials or just guess. They've tried to compensate for this by having guidance stuff at the beginning of every campaign you do, which gets pretty annoying if you've done it before. I think they could have combined the combat tutorials with a properly interactive warband tutorial to make a mini-campaign which would have been much more engaging.My main beef, however, with this game is the probabilities. Over my time playing it, I would say that 70-80% hit chances come off less than half the time. Perhaps I've been incredibly unlucky, but that's my experience. At best it makes the combat laborious as you wait for the whole turn cycle to go around again before you can attempt another hit. At worst, it screws you over as the opposition then piles a load of extra soldiers in to the combat and you lose all advantage that you had."
76561198007729622,Not Recommended,276810,21629156,"Posted: 4 March, 2016",all,Matty Stardust,"I really like this game, it's addictive and is fun to play up to a point. But it is so demanding constantly, needing to earn gold to pay your warband, collect wyrdstones to send shipments and being constantly aware that one battle could be the end of your warband perminantly, even a technical win could result in a overall loss if some of your key members get poor RNG results at the end and end up loosing an arm or other injuries.While I do like the demanding nature of the campaign it makes the game something you can't really play when you're not paying full attention and it makes it feel not so much like fun to me. If they were able to introduce a way you could have duel profiles, one you could play seriously and was as it is now brutal, and one where things were more relaxed but not easy I think I would start recommending my friends to get this game rather than steer clear for now."
