rs suck and die through countless horrible rolls of the dice.  10/10- I must be lucky! I missed that attack with a 95% chance to hit!"
76561198015070706,Recommended,276810,29123597,Posted: 8 January,all,DEATHJABBERS,"8.5/10. This is a very good game. Many people are leaving negative comments that are based entirely on ignorance.Things you should know before buying; this game:* has a VERY PRONOUNCED KNOWLEDGE BARRIER. It may take over 20 hours of gameplay to truly understand the game's mechanics. For this reason I would suggest not putting much stock in gameplay reviews from people who have under 20 hours of gameplay time.- has a similar feel to the original Mordheim board game. It's obviously very different, but it retains its namesake's tactical and challenging appeal.- is of a similar vein to XCOM. Mordheim does have a lot more punching, and a lot less shooting.- has a luck component. It is very fair and balanced. The game does not cheat you. Others say that the game actively cheats you; they are both ignorant and incorrect. They do not have a solid understanding of the game mechanics. I have seen statements like the following: ""The game said i had a 95% chance to hit, and I missed three times in a row!"". This scenario is entirely possible. The % hit chance does not entirely reflect the target's avoidance. Literally every statement that I have seen which disparages the game's luck component originate from stances which are both ignorant and incorrect, and are similar to what I stated above.- is VERY challenging/unforgiving. Especially if you do not have a very solid grasp of the game mechanics. Almost every turn you take with each of your units has to be well planned and executed. One miss-step could mean a total loss, either of your character or the whole campaign. Also, there is NO saving. Everything is permanent and irreversible.- does NOT tell you how to play itself, and never explains anything. The tutorial is worthless. You really need to read every aspect of the character sheets to get acquainted with the layout, and then go on the forums and read up on how everything works in-game.That being said, the game is very fun and rewarding. There is no more problems with loading times. The enemy units do now go after wyrdstone. The AI enemies do play their turns out in real time and may take ~1 minute, so if you are *extremely* impatient, you might want to keep this in mind,I rated this game an 8.5/10 because, while it is very good, it has a few noticeably detracting flaws:-Occasionally buggy AI. Perhaps 1 in every 10 games, an AI unit will glitch and stand in a corner. When this happens, the entire balance of the game is destroyed. Even losing 1 unit in a 10 vs. 10 battle is crippling. When this happens, the match's enjoyment is entirely gone. This is the major detractor.-Often poor AI. The AI are not a match for the player, in terms of skill and tactics. 'Harder' missions are simply ones where the AI units have better gear, more stats, and more abilities than your units. Your tactics might change on harder difficulties, but there is absolutely no scaling in tactical difficulty.-Antiquated looking graphics. While acceptable, the graphics are sub-par when compared to games of the same generation.I would only recommend this game if you like a challenging, tactical, and rewarding experience, and you don't mind defeat. Because defeat will happen. Early and often.If you are a rabid fan of WHFB. and this game's affiliation with WHFB is your primary selling point, then get it. You'll be tickled pink. Just don't try to get too attached to your warband; as I said, they will die =P"
76561198007707387,Recommended,276810,29288498,Posted: 15 January,all,dalecki2,"It's good, my favorite of the X-COM-alikes. I played Skaven, Empire, and Undead and progressed until I had a level 10-ish warband in each. A few pros and cons:Pros:1. Races feel distinct and none feels too strong or too weak. Weapons and armor feel balanced.2. The game does a good job in making you use tactics and the environment to win over an enemy that will almost always be stronger than you are. As Empire, I had a clump of ranged that moved around and focused individual stragglers or used chokepoints while my tanks took damage. As Skaven, I was mobile enough to converge first in the missions where you start out in separate packs. As Undead, i'd have zombies distract and occupy enemies while my crypt horror and vampires focused the rest down.3. RNG is just right for me. Part of tactical games is to have a backup for your tactic; if my 85% chance to hit guy misses...what do I do? I've never had those one in a million streaks some of these other commenters have. One in a thousand? Sure. But not one in a million.Cons:1. Campaign missions aren't very good. Endless waves of reinforcements while you try to get that last objective.2. AI will get stuck on stuff. The large creatures especially will get stuck on stuff. That ends up giving a lot of variance to the difficulty.3. Many of the skills are almost never worth using.Overall pretty good and worth buying (maybe on 50% sale, those come around fairly often)."
