76561198032109696,Recommended,276810,31752249,Posted: 14 May,all,Godsaid,"I like this game a lot.  The graphics and mechanics are top notch.  Warbands are highly customizable and the different factions each play differently enough to give it a very high replayability rating.  However...this game is probably not for those gamers of a certain temperment.  The constant challenging setbacks and the devilish RNG can frustrate the bejeezus outta you.-- Your warriors WILL get knocked out, suffer permanent injury and death, and undergo unfavorable mutations.  It will happen to your most skilled warrior or your newest rookie henchman without discretion.  If you do your best not to put your best units at risk and let the fodder get punished first, you can prevent some, but not all, of the tragedy.--  You will lose good weapons and armor when the crap hits the fan, as the enemy loots your stuff and takes it.--  You will lose battles and you will fail to deliver on missions.--  You will get caught out of position and in the open and be surrounded and isolated on maps, but you can turn these battles around with some skill and some luck.--  If you adapt and learn, you will get better at managing initiative, positioning, tactics, equipping characters, training, etc.Drawbacks are a big part of Mordheim.  It adds dark humor, constant challenge and a foreboding, ominous flavor to the game.  These are not reasons to dislike this game, but the reason you should play it."
76561198117822028,Recommended,276810,33512314,Posted: 13 July,all,camperion,"Mordheim is not for everyone. Its unforgiving, slow-paced, and grindy. There is no save-scumming, permanent death/injuries, RNG, and the chance to lose a great deal of progress with a single error. After you figure out the mechanics and rhythm of the game those things are more limitations on your progress, instead of significant impediments.Its main drawback is a result of the nature of the single save and the punishment for failure. These are good mechanics and needed for the dark setting of Mordheim, but ultimately forces you to rely on a single strategy for all standards missions. Essentially, there is no good reason to ever take risks or seek out you enemy--it ALWAYS makes more sense to pick a good defensive spot near spawn (making sure to always pick missions with a tight deployment) and wait for the AI to trickle its fighters into your ambush. While the potential for RNG can still get your warriors killed if you are careless, this strategy essentially decides all your standard missions. Thus instead of a highly strategic game, it often feels like a tedious game of waiting for the AI to rush to its death. The story missions are different, and show a glimmer of how difficult this game could be if you were forced to fight the AI in a more aggressive fashion.All that said, this game is weirdly fun to play. All the factions share similar mechanics but play significantly different. The customization isn't great or expansive, but enough to feel attached to your warriors who have the potential to acquire grizzly injuries. Progressing your warband is an achievement mostly of the player's patience, but rewarding all the same.Overall I think its a great game to pick up when it goes on sale (which it does with regularity)."
