,Not Recommended,276810,22563721,"Posted: 22 April, 2016",all,Oathed,"I can't in good conscience recommend this game to anyone but the hardcore fans of the genre or Warhammer or turn-based squad tactics. The game development appears to have been farmed out, over-promised, feature-creep is everywhere, and there's bugs and invisible walls and glitches and a horrible map system and cluttered UI.Reasons not to buy:* Invisible walls* The single worst deployment system/mechanics I've seen in any game, ever. Disorienting, hopelessly inept and repetitive. Had one mission start with 40+ spots, and had to cycle through them one by one with 6 characters, while camera angle went flying without rhyme or reason. Nuts.* Can't move through obviously large enough spaces* Can't move past tiny little ledges* Can't jump down from a ledge that looks super easy to get down from, with no obstructions whatsoever. These game designers valued looks over playability, by a lot. Goddammit people.* Can't drop items from inventory* Little guidance to the new player, other than ""You should have noticed the tutorials on the first screen, and played through each of them individually."" Come on, that's no way to treat a new player who knows nothing about your game.* Skills and equipment are unbalanced and confusing.* There's little explanation of what different icons mean.* There's no easy way to figure out on which level of a 3-storey house a Search Point is, unless you're close to it and pass a Perception check, which is a pain and slows down movement. Especially early on with a very low percentage chance to pass the stupid test.* Doing bonus objectives means you get Exp faster, but not much gold faster, which means your dudes are higher level but can't afford to train new skills. The enemy computer doesn't care about gold to train skills, he just comes with fully trained troops same level as you. So - doing optional objectives is really just shooting yourself in the foot. Grind it out, slow and steady. Play the long game.* Using the UI in town and in combat is confusing and miserable, at best.* Repetitive buff and debuff ""pauses"" and graphic animations. That's just annoying as f. Do one thing, wait for the pause, wait for the animation, wait for the pause, wait for the next thing. Come on.* 4 warbands and some DLC specials, compared to the variety and awesomeness that is Warhammer Fantasy, or the original Mordheim. They overpromised on graphics and visuals and animations and thus had to skimp on warbands, and as this is a niche game for niche people and old guys like me, there's not enough money flowing in for more warbands. It's a B budget game for a B budget audience.* The AI is just dumb. Don't even bother calling it AI - it's just rush and attack and that's it.* The difficulty level of the game relies PURELY on RNG percentage stacking. Make things risky enough in dice rolls and eventually you'll have a string of crits against the player and he'll have no chance. There's little in the way of interesting behaviour of the computer.* The game doesn't reward beating your enemies or even fighting them. It's much more important to avoid your enemies for as long as possible, even leaving them alive when you could have ""won"" the scenario quickly - instead just focus on sneaking around the map and gathering wyrdstone and hitting the ""Search Points"". What a knockered design. They tried to fix it by giving the player who wins some of the loot left behind, but it's far from enough to make you a good player if you just focus on winning the scenario. You really really need to sneak around and avoid engaging in a fight. Oh well.Reasons to buy:* You're a sucker for anything Warhammer or turn-based, like me.* Some stuff is kind of cool, the rest is just annoying.* There is multiplayer, so if you have friends or don't mind communicating with random people and building up a community, yes you can. I'm not personally a fan of random people on the internet, but maybe you are.* It's Mordheim, one of the coolest, longest-running franchises in gaming history."
