76561197973057598,Not Recommended,276810,29798535,Posted: 9 February,all,mikeerty,"I really want to like this game.I love the permadeath and character progression. I love the permanent injuries and the brutal fighting.I played it in early access and I remember thinking the game was cheating me on the To Hit rolls. 90% chance to hit missing 9 times out of ten. What wasn't made clear (and still isn't, unless you're looking for it) is that yes you may pass the To Hit roll 90% of the time, but there's another roll that takes place simultaneously. If you hit, the enemy usually has a chance to dodge or block. If they're really agile they'll dodge maybe half the time. Therfore you feel like you're missing again and again, when actually your sodlier did his part and the enemy jumped out the way.The combat log tracks all the rolls, which helps ease the feeling of being robbed.But that isn't my biggest gripe!In the campaign you're thrown to the wolves immediately, and in a game so heavily reliant on stats and percentages it's just hopelessly unfair unless you're very lucky. It's like the video game version of Monopoly.Each ""day"" you pick a mission. They're random in difficulty. The enemies in the mission are random too. On day two I had only 2 choices - a Lethal mission and a Deadly mission. I used the scouting button to find another few missions - both pretty much promised failure.Thinking this was just the game adding some fluff I headed into the least dangerous one.I gathered my team and held my ground, hoping to mob the enemy. Except I couldn't because their warband was so much better than mine. My hero would lose over half his health to a single enemy henchman strike (not even critical). My hero and leader had to hit the enemy henchmen around 8 times before they died. Numerically it was impossible, despite surrounding them and trying to pick them off. At a certain point The Numbers dictate the overall outcome.This is made worse when you realise there are permanent injuries (a good idea in theory) AND time limits for completing shipments which you can only miss 4 of before you fail the game. You HAVE to get into missions, and when those missions are guaranteed to be a disaster I felt like the victim of overly cruel game design. Why not scale the enemy warbands up with you? Why would you ever put the player into a positiion where they are up against brutal, deadly or lethal warbands on day 2?Some people seem to love this game and relish the difficulty, so I recommend it for people who are drawn to that kind of challenge. But I think most people probably don't want to have to go digging and scraping around the internet for tips and exploits (like, ""Don't ever play story missions because they're broken and have infinite waves of enemies"" and ""avoid missions where there's a chance you could be spread out because it's almost a guranteed fail as the enemy will intercept your guys and pick them off one by one before you can regroup""). If I have to cordon off portions of a game because it's broken or unbalanced then they've done something wrong."
