76561198025200773,Not Recommended,276810,24298002,"Posted: 13 July, 2016",all,Ningasak,"I picked this game up on sale. I have to admit I'm a huge Warhammer fan from the wayback. When all the armies had one book and one gear list.This game is fun at first...Then as you advance further into the game it just keeps punishing you for trying. Let me explain. The developers made this hardcore, or 'Ironman' mode for you xcom players. They also included a wound system kind of like in blood bowl. If one of your team gets 'knocked out' they roll on the wound table. The possible outcomes are slight injury, no harm done, or a wound. These add a negative quality and then a slight positive trait or, (and this is a big or) OR your unit dies. In bloodbowl you can buy things that let you re-roll some of these in game effects. Rather than letting your star player die you can use a token, in the form of a team doctor, to re-roll. There are also re-rolls. This game however, spits in your face like a insane difficulty xcom 2 match. There is no way to reroll you just take whatever ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t it hands you.So that's not a huge deal. Units die, hardcore is cool right?Too bad this game forces you to grind like are a lap-dancer for 2 xp a mission (10 for level 1 and it scales up). A few things increase this total but in general you have to play normal mission safely grinding away. To do this you have to pay for scouts to get normal missions because they randomly assign missions. Even then enemy units have the ability to pick off a unit on the first or second round from poor starting positions and wounding occurs. This means you epic level 9 hero with bad♥♥♥♥♥skills just lost a leg or died. I'm assuming at some point late game you can just re-purchase units of higher level and this loss isn't so huge but at the level of gameplay I got to this basically junks my warband. At least in x-com when you lose, you lose. Like you can't fight the aliens win, story over. This game just leaves you with a warband full of corpses then gives you spare change to re-purchase units or start the grind all over again.I really wanted to like this game but it just doesn't reward, unlock, or present any new challenges. After a few matches you begin to see a trend in the game play. Same match, some crappy city map with bad jumps and dead ends caused by slightly ajar doors. Which has not been flustrating for just myself, as more than one review is plagued by complaints about terrain that just doesn't make sense. Seriously why can't I open a door...Finally, the last thing I feel the need to complain about is the terrible customization tool. They offer only 1 type of slot item in most areas, so 'one' helmet or lack there-of, as a choice. The colors are not set to colors, they are values, so helmet on, then color 1. These colors don't always match, like 16 isn't always blue for example. Sometimes 16 is a pink. Like the designers painted the units in colors, then set values to each paint job. The designers clearly thought that a blue and pink combo is a 16....This customization tool is junk and should have been scrapped, it makes xcom 2 look like they are master skin crafters rather than meth'ed Halloween costume designing rejects.Moral of the story...save your money. I’d buy it for $10 but only if I played too much bloodbowl."
76561197976682879,Not Recommended,276810,23961587,"Posted: 30 June, 2016",all,steevm,"I really wanted to like this game, and I am sure it is great if you are willing to invest a lot of time into learning it. Unfortunately, the difficulty level - at least for noobs with no experience of the TT game - is insane. Now for some people, that will be the appeal, and I say good luck to them. To other people - count me among them - if a game is too difficult, especially when starting out, it's a massive turn-off. I want to feel like I am progressing and learning the game while also feeling like I have a chance to win. With Mordheim, I never once felt like there was a chance that I was going to win a battle (I got totally wiped out each time I tried), and never once did I feel in control over the way things were going.I am sure that youcaninflucence events once you have got into the swing of things and learn how to exploit the AI's deficiencies. The question you need to ask yourself is: are you ever going to get to that point in the game? If you want ironman challenge from the start, and don't mind starting a new game every half an hour or so, then ignore this review and buy the game if it sounds like your thing. If you prefer a gradual progression and the ability to ramp up the difficulty later once you have a grasp of the basic mechanics, steer well clear. Chances are high that you will ragequit and not come back.The reason I asked for a refund is not because I hate difficult games, or have an issue with no save-scumming and permadeath (I've been playing nethack et al since before most of you were born), or don't like complex games. I do, but I like them to draw me in and give me the feeling of progression and an ability to influence events. Mordheim failed to do either of those for me. It ticks all the boxes for me, but just didn't click.So this thumbs down isn't so much a ""OMFG this game S|_|XX0R"" but a warning to other players who may be on the fence about whether to purchase it or not. You want to be sure that this is really your cup of tea. I also appreciate that with <2 hours of playtime, my opinion is hardly well formed, but that's the cut off period for steam refunds and I don't feel like I am going to come back to this one."
