76561198139666948,Not Recommended,276810,29298949,Posted: 16 January,all,Jexsam31,"I bought Mordheim thinking it would be a fun but challenging squad based tactical RPG, it was not. The reason that it’s not stems from a couple of factors, the first one is the rng, on numerous occasions, I found myself missing far more than I should. A great example is during one fight, I failed 4 80% to hit checks in a row, hit once, and missed again. I very frequently got the impression that the number I was being shown for my hit chance was simply wrong. This applies to all elements of the game that are left to chance (and there are many). The next issue is that the enemies you fight will typically be so far out of your league that you won’t be able to win 4 on 1 encounters. I am not exaggerating, when I first started playing, a hero ,a leader,  and 2 of my henchmen lost in a fight with a vampire, they kept failing their fear checks (preventing them from being useful), and kept getting hit. Even in my more recent fights with vampires, I almost lost, I had a vampire lord outnumbered 5 to 1, and it took nearly 3 turns to kill him, he never once failed his all alone checks (I don’t even think he went through any for some reason), and even had enough points to use a skill to lower all of my defensive options for all of my soldiers and do 3 attacks in a row, which he almost never missed. This issue applies to all enemies, not just the vampires, but they were the encounters I remembered the most clearly, and were my kryptonite for some reason. I can’t recommend the game; it’s not that the game is too hard, but that it simply wants to artificially inflate your death count and failures by screwing you. You can start again, hire new soldiers to replace the crippled or dead ones, but it screws you because your new soldiers start out at base level, meaning that their overall combat utility is significantly lower than that of the rest of your squad, and you will suffer for it.If you still want to play this game, here are some tips; don’t take missions above the hard difficulty setting, try to save up your wyrdstone for a rainy day or required shipment, play the tutorials, always try to move as a massed force or decent sized squads, and focus more on keeping your squad alive than the secondary objectives. Also, be careful about charging, if there are any obstacles in the way your character will simply move forward and do nothing, wasting your offence points. One more thing, if your enemy is moving as a massed force, try to kill them one at a time, as quickly as possible and keep them pinned down or blocked, that or lose, those are your options for fighting massed enemy forces.Over my time playing, I’ve used ¾ of the original factions, gone through at least 5 maps with each, played 2 story missions, played around 40-50 maps in total (including the tutorials), and at the time of this review, put around 30 hours into this game.In summary, the game isn’t bad, but it’s not very rewarding because it typically punishes you in ways that seem unfair, be it a single enemy being able to kill most of your party, or the rng screwing you more than you can comprehend."
