76561197985847263,Recommended,276810,24836657,"Posted: 11 August, 2016",all,[LoR] Team Triss,"It's XCOM without the grid and with a handful of options forced on you.  If you like playing Ironman Classic (or above), you will like this game, otherwise you very likely won't.The RNG is 100% completely fair, the AI has to abide by the same game rules that you do with 2 exceptions:1) It gets a 35% bonus to Stupidity (a roll a wounded character might have to make in order to get a turn) checks, since it cannot effectively use the appropriate skill to boost the chance2) Depending on mission difficulty (Normal, Hard, Brutal, Deadly), it gets a bonus of increments of 10% to hit and to its total HP value, but I don't believe Deadly gets +40% to each.Beware, as the game has a very steep learning curve.  I found the tutorials to be sufficient, but don't be afraid to ask questions on the forums.  The forums are a nice bunch and generally very friendly, though I caution you against going into them and raging against how unfair the RNG is (it isn't) or some other well-debunked nonsense.  The game is hard, although losses are not always a bad thing.  I am not sure character death is a thing, as I've not encountered it; a far more common outcome is permanent injuries, should one of your characters suffer a critical hit or be knocked out completely, there's a chance they'll lose some gear and/or suffer a permanent injury, forever affecting stats.  You are in total control of your warband, though, and can hire and fire people at will.  Your scout has a peg leg?  Can him and train up a replacement.Don't come in expecting AAA flash and content.  It's a small studio who are trying their damnedest and they're doing a fantastic job, but there are 4 warbands in the base game with a fifth available as DLC.  Each warband has it's own campaign, which is a series of faction-specific missions buried in the main campaign: a map that spawns random missions.  Gathering a green crystal called Wyrdstone is your primary objective, as the only way to fail the campaign outright is to miss a total of four shipments to your warband's benefactor.  The game is pretty enough and has good sound design, but can be slightly clunky at times, especially in character movement.Think long and hard before you pick it up.  If it immediately strikes you as something you'd like, knowing full well that it will give you a swift kick in the nethers, then pick it up, as you won't be disappointed.  If you're on the fence, however, I recommend staying away."
