76561198022721707,Not Recommended,276810,26586493,"Posted: 13 November, 2016",all,sikkwolf,"Update: I have now spent many, many more hours with the game. My opinion is unchanged. I love strategy games, I love the warhammer universe, and I really want to love Mordheim. I can't though, because the game is clearly bent.I just went on a 20 win streak against the AI because I forced myself to forgo searching ruins or collecting stones as the primary focus of my excursions and instead focused solely on bottle necking the enemy and mobbing their team one by one as they tried to get into whatever trench I sat and waited for them in. The game is very, very easy when you play like that, because even though at 4 on 1 odds the RNG and designer bias (seriously, +30% wounds just because?) towards the AI is palpable, it's not enough to destroy your fun.That streak ended the first time I got too comfortable and didn't follow my own advice, open conflict with the AI in this game is laden with blatant weighting to the point it's incredulous. I watched in outright anger as my characters repeatedly missed strikes at 95% success chances, boiling down to an overall real success rate of 37% by the time the game decided to route me. The AI controlled warband on the other hand, only missed 4 times in the entire exchange, 2 of them were on a warrior that their impressive only need to hit once to retire, the third attack landed, not because that's how the dice roll, but because that's how you hide blatant weighting.I was also hostage to two scenarios where it let the AI's soldier counter attack my engaging character before letting me attack them to begin with. Mordheim is a lot of things, fun is one of them if you're the kind of dullard that is okay with playing every match the same way, over and over. I personally, again, want to love Mordheim, because it has all the hallmarks of a classic small team tactics game. Unfortunately, it also has all the negative attributes of a crapfest thanks to the developers being more concerned with making things hard on you over providing an enjoyable experience.I cannot give the game a good review even though I'm still playing it and will likely buy the expansion material, because wish I'd never purchased/played it; that is due to the fact that overall it's like dating a pretty girl, that's fun, but has tons of negative baggage and a psychotic streak. You stay because you want the fantasy where everything is right to play out, and it does occasionally, but the reality is that you should leave asap because there is more wrong here than right, and the longer you stay the worse it's going to get for you.For people who love the Ironman runs in XCOM this game is probably right up your alley. It just isn't something I really got into. Take the review for what it is, my opinion................................................Original......................................................Positive reviews for games like this confound me, because I know for a fact that the gaming base by far and large is not made up of masochists, though it is arguably made up of idiots.Mordheim has a lot in common with xcom, fun is not among those things however. The RNG in the game may in fact even out, as it allegedly does with xcom, but there is no room for tactical mitigation to this abusive mechanism. I actually did grow up playing Rifts, D&D, and Warhammer (as well as the entire White Wolf game world). Bad runs with dice happen, but never at the frequency they do in these games. I spent 3 hours today playing Mordheim on the Xbox One, it was three hours I spend screaming at the TV and scaring my kids because the game put me in such a rage I couldn't even interact with them positively, and not because I'm a sore loser.Every deployment, I was scattered, every deployment I missed nearly all my attacks while the enemy landed all of theirs, it felt like a Warhammer themed remake of ""The Warriors"" by the end as I realized, like all games, you're in the dark but the AI is not, and as my characters got scattered every sortie, in an attempt to regroup them, smaller groups of my weakest warriors were regularly set upon by their heroes and company, rare did they take any damage, I would lose all my warriors in each exchange due to chronic strings of ""bad luck"".If you feel compelled to write a positive review for this because you're just one of those guys that needs to pretend he's part of that 1337 crew, great, good for you, we both know how fake your opinion is. This game sucks, horribly, I would really, really enjoy a true Warhammer game that really brings about the glory, brutality, tactics, and most of all F U N that is associated with the miniatures based table top game."
