76561197997047650,Not Recommended,276810,19579167,"Posted: 9 December, 2015",all,mcgregor,"Moments of fun are reduced to rubble by poor AI, limited tactics, and questionable design choices.Positives+ Campaign progression is addictive (enough to get many people past the steam refund window).+ You get attached to your squad as they improve, lose limbs, and die (not always in that order).+ Permanent ironman mode and rolls of the dice keep even easier battles tense.Negatives- Poor enemy AI- Lack of real tactics - outnumber your opponent to win- Enemies auto level to make up for the AI.  Remember Oblivion?  This saps the meaning out of progression. The enemy is always a little, and sometimes a lot stronger, though hampered by random skills.  This makes for dull battles of attrition as you whittle away their health bars.- The enemy number is always the same as your own, with similar numbers of heroes or henchman.  Urban combat between scavengers shouldn't feel like organized sports.- Story missions are focused on tedious inventory management and a lot of running around very large, mostly empty maps. Put the ball in the net gameplay.  With uneven pacing and game ending bugs still lurking inside of them, they feel tacked on.- Secondary objectives don't make sense.  Why can't we collect bounties after the fight?  Why are we fleeing the scene so quickly when the point is to scavenge for loot and wyrdstone?  It contributes to the refereed sports feel.- There are very few viable build options per faction.  Most builds are inferior and you will be punished for trying them.    It is a puzzle to be solved, no more.  Chose the best skills and you will succeed because the AI chooses randomly.--- Rant: The game is very ""inside the box"", very gamey, like organized sports rather than medieval combat.   Why can't we raid the wyrdstone caravans that are streaming out of the city?  Or why can't we set up shop as trainers and make some real money?  (When in the history of the Warhammer universe (or any other universe) did teachers make so much flippin' money?)   How about a campaign structure based upon more than a couple battles to chose from?  Why did my warband decide to ambush the enemy, when that would clearly mean certain death due to dividing my forces? (Encirclement really only works when numerically superior - something that can never happen in this universe.)  Why can't we retreat when the odds are clearly against us?  Must we be pummeled first?  Because of... Rules?  Why can't we take one turn to pick up wyrdstone, trinkets, or loot at the end of the battle?  Coach, must we march off the field to the showers before collecting our roses?!  I don't care if something might show up.  My men just risked their lives to grab pocketfuls of wyrdstone in a pitched battle.  Now they can't take another 5 minutes to toss the rest in the cart.  I call BS.  Willing suspension of disbelief only goes so far.  It just throws GAME in your face at every opportunity: too much Bloodbowl balance and not enough urban warfare chaos.Mordheim has its moments. There are better options.  I was playing Battle Brothers before I gave this a try.  For medieval warband management and deadly turn-based tactical combat, that game is superior."
