,Not Recommended,276810,13029258,"Posted: 21 November, 2014",all,Hollywood,"It pains me to not recommend the game but I feel like I must. I love GW games, and I think this game has great potential. That being said, I hate the fact of early access or ""paid betas."" Sure I asked for it by buying the game but basically at this stage you can only do one match, Skaven vs Mercs or Mercs vs Skaven. The game was fun however the current replay value just isn't there yet. I am sure in the next few months this game will become extremely fun and entertaining as the promises get fulfilled (fingers crossed) but until then, basically all you're buying is a loan to the developers/publishers. Give them $31.99 and they will give you $5 worth of game that may appreciate in value over time to what they expect it to be worth $39.99.***UPDATED***RA0H,I thank you for taking the time in responding to my review and I noticed you guys are taking an initiative to respond to reviews on a very granular level and I respect that. I can assure you that nothing is certain in such a fickle business and I doubt the game is fully funded and you only have the pure intention of getting feedback. If that’s the case why charge, why isn’t it free then when the full game is released it costs money? Video gamers for some reason make terrible decisions (like yours truly) with their buying power. I am sure everyone has heard of product testing and consumer feedback especially when you are kids. I remember growing up always hearing rumors of companies like Mattel offering kids money to play with unreleased toys and letting them know what you liked and disliked about them. You think when a movie company or a toy company asks consumers for feedback on unreleased products they go, “hey would you mind playing with this toy and telling me what you think about it? It’s going to MSRP for $19.99 but I will sell it to you for $15.99 then we can talk about what you like and dislike about it?” No? Or how about, “come watch this movie and tell me what you think, by the way I am going to need $10 from you when you get a chance…Oh you want popcorn too, five more dollars please.” Nope, doesn’t happen. These companies pay for the feedback, provide snacks, as well as a physical location to have the testing and feedback session. Now here we have the gaming industry and you get the advantage of having a digital platform for distribution. No facility is required to house such testing and you don’t have to provide PCs for your potential consumers. But don’t let the cost cutting stop there, we might as well get paid to allow them the privilege to tell us how much we suck or don’t suck. But why stop there? These people already bought the game unreleased, do day one DLC, you can also just not fulfill promises by release, then later fill them by releasing more DLC. It’s a cash grab, something that GW is most certainly familiar with and I for one feel like this is the most authentic GW tabletop to video game translation because you got the most familiar and ever so persisting thing about GW games. The sting of their amazing cash grabs."
