,Recommended,276810,20418199,"Posted: 9 January, 2016",all,Cawpikolo,"Fantastic game and one of the more unique games I have played in the past few years.Story is simple very rich city goes to♥♥♥♥♥♥when a huge meteor comes in and decimates everything. Demons pop out of it and start eating people. 4 factions come in and start killing each other for control over the precious materials that was left by the meteor.All factions are unique in their own way the rat people or skaven are usually very good at dodging. They excel in swarm tactics meaning you want 4 guys on one and beat him into the ground before stealing his wallet. The majority of their faction skills also support this play style by debuffing opponent's offense points with poison per hit. Their weakness however is of course they're low on hp or ""wounds"" and their range is absolute♥♥♥♥♥♥where all they have are ninja stars. Their impressive is great but the rat ogre is as stupid as a pile of bricks possibly dumber since he can spend 3-4 turns sitting in a corner taking a♥♥♥♥♥♥while the rest of your army is getting beat to death by women with hammers the size of babies.The sisters of mercy are very ironic in which they have no range whatsoever and concentrate on going in heavy and crushing people under their hammers. They have no range troops but have helpful spells. Their impressive unit is a woman blessed by sigmar that does large amounts of damage.The reikland or average joes are just your regular band of boys coming in to make it rich. The got guns guns and guns but they can go in heavy. They can use spells as well. I usually go with two riflemen and several swordsmen. Doesn't really work since the sisters bashed my face in on multiple occasions. Their impressive is an ogre I am not sure he has a stupidity check since I never made it that far.The chaos are the most unique in my opinion. I have not tried them but from what i've seen they have a wide array of attack spells and do high damage with double handed weapons. They also seem to be able to pledge allegiance to one of the chaos gods. I have seen heroes that are blessed by tzeench, khorne,nurgle and slaneesh where their bodies are actually morphed in a way to make it obvious what allegiance they hold. Their impressive is a chaos spawn a big ugly gray fella that like to mount and hump anything that moves.There are also neutral monsters that pop up every now and again I have only bumped into a blood letter and chaos ogre. Either way they ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥up. The blood letter is so buff my first attacks usually bounced off his rock hard abs and did no damage. He would then cleave through two of my men at the same time and start screaming. The chaos ogre I just sat in the corner and cried while he beat my opponent's army into the ground.The positives are this game has a high amount of customization.-You can customize your army down to their appearance.-The turn based gameplay is fun and the missions mix things up well. The graphics are also visually appealing.-You will actually care about your troops since they are an incredibly large investment. Depending on their skills and equipment a soldier can cost over 1000 gold.-Unique injury system where when your men get knocked out they can lose limbs or have injuries that follow them they can either be positive or negative. Losing an arm gains 20% dodge a person but they can't use two handed weapons. An injury causes bravery where disengaging is no longer possible for a person this can also be bad for tactical retreats. I have one of my Scatmen (skaven rat) lose an arm during a mission. I renamed him stumpy and now he dodges every attack and♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥people with his toothpick. He is now a veteran of over 30 battles.There are also a lot of negatives with this game.- some missions when you deploy your enemies can deploy right next to you. I lost a captain before I was even able to move when he was beat down by two sisters of mercy that deployed by my wagon. Deployment areas will be implemented soon where I can choose where to put a soldier in a box rather than choose an individual position.-In higher difficulties the enemy gets huge stat boosts and enemy stupidity checks are no longer existent while yours seem to fail every single time.- You are unable to continue looting after the battle is over. That means when you win you do not get everything off the map. This also means if one of your men gets downed and an enemy loots him just before they fail rout check consider whatever they stole gone. I lost a few thousand gold in equipment because of that.-Shipments do not raise reputation with your faction. With the wyrdstone function sometimes your faction leader will ask you to send wyrdstones. There is also several other factions you can sell wyrdstone to this all adds into a reputation system where you are granted bonuses for how much you give to the factions. The problem with this is when your faction leader asks for a shipment you gain no reputation whatsoever for fulfilling it. On top of that it gets bigger as your warband levels up without raising the wyrdstone drop on maps. So now you're stuck with getting 400-500 wyrdstone sold at a price where you're faction leader is seriously sodomizing you and your men (50-60% of actual value.) to put it short you need to send wyrdstone to level up your reputation but your faction leader asks for large shipments of wyrdstone every other day that is mandatory or you lose the game but those shipments do not raise reputation. see the problem here? a big cycle of ♥♥♥♥ was made there where you ♥♥♥♥ up factions in mordheim then your faction leader ♥♥♥♥s you."
