76561198042253283,Recommended,276810,21035357,"Posted: 7 February, 2016",all,Jasan Quinn,"This game is not your friend. It is difficult and brutally unforgiving. Victory lies in being able to juggle risk and reward, both in battle and in the smuggling contracts.To explain, your warband is on the clock. Every so often you are given x turns to amass y weight of wyrdstone. Fail to meet the quota four times and you lose the campaign. Problem is, it can take 3-5 days for party members to recover from injuries, learn new skills, etc. A day spent healing is a day not earning wyrdstone, but to rush into battle with an ill-prepared warband can be equally disasterous.In game, the same problem arises. The only way to amass a lot of wyrdstone is to scavenge for it, but good scavenging sites are often spread far apart and require you to take risks to reach them. Many a mission has gone south because my warband was spread thin looting and not formed up for battle.If you like permanent consequences on your characters, an AI that pulls no punches, and games that never let you rest easy, then Mordheim has that in spades. The only downside is that it's not exactly relaxing to play, so find something calm and soothing to do after you find someone hacked your leader's arm off."
