76561198021765481,Recommended,276810,27530507,"Posted: 25 November, 2016",all,Meeky,"Never before have I played a game that made me so angry and yet made me love it so much. It's a turn-based strategy with RPG elements that will make you want to punch someone out of frustration while at once making you yearn for MORE. If that intrigues you, read on.Mordheim is a game that I can't play all the time, but when I do, I really and truly immerse myself into it. The basis is that there's a city, Mordheim, that brought the apocalypse on itself, and various powers throughout the world have descended on its ruins like carrion to a corpse. You are leading a warband of such a group, and you're out to achieve your goals by mauling anyone else that comes close to the precious Wyrdstone that everyone wants.The story itself is a weak point of the game - or, rather, not the point at all. The point of the game is in the strategy, the brutality of gameplay, and in struggling to keep your warband afloat when terrible things can happen at any given moment.See, this is a turn-based strategy, as I said, and it's got RPG elements in the form of your characters. You end up investing a lot into your characters, and you try to keep them from being knocked out in a fight. If they get knocked out, they may suffer permanent injuries: eye loss, arm loss, leg loss, stupidity from concussions, cracked skulls, psychological disorders... you name it. They can also die from their injuries, though some of these injuries are just as effective as having a dead character sometimes. And the real danger is that since the game has some RNG inherent to its system AND you're always fighting warbands of either equal or greater strength, this can leave you wanting to throw the keyboard across the room and stalk the streets of your neighborhood looking for something to strangle.Assuming you can control that bloodlust and channel it toward the game itself, though, you'll have a blast.There's a lot of depth to building your characters, both in equipment and in stats. You learn a lot from your playthroughs, discovering what sort of builds will work for what roles, what sort of builds you wish you hadn't tried, and you'll observe the enemy's warriors and think ""Wow, that's a cool ability that I should try."" You'll find yourself experimenting a lot (as much as you can afford to, anyway). Finding the faction whose playstyle suits you best is an adventure, too; and sometimes you'll realize that a certain synergy between units - such as the Vampire Counts warband with Poison Globadiers, or a Smuggler to shore up the ranged weakness of the Sisters of Sigmar - just feels right.One particular talent that you can get I want to make special note of: ""The Lad's Got Talent."" If you get a Hired Sword minion (read: a mook-level character) with enough character levels (say, 5+), you can potentially get the elite version of The Lad's Got Talent while statting them up. This means they can end up taking a Hero slot and have a LOT of really juicy ability and attribute points to throw around for free. It's one of those nifty things you can discover in the character building process that makes the game that much complex and fun to theorycraft for.Setting up situations where you can minimize damage to your group can be a challenge, though it's less of a challenge in single player. You'll start your battles off by scouting and figuring out where the enemy is most times, then trying to attack them in such a way that you won't get counterattacked too hard (such as taking out a small group of scouts before gathering your forces for a pitched battle that now favors you). You'll be sending a couple folks around gathering the oh-so-precious Wyrdstone that brings you the money you need to survive Mordheim. I've sacrificed some warriors for the sake of getting enough Wyrdstone to see another day, for sure.Finally, remember that this is an unforgiving game. You can't get too attached to your characters - one critical hit too many might result in them being in the morgue far sooner than you'd like. Other times you'll have someone become so crippled that having them in your warband actually feels like a detriment, and you decide it's time to put that horse to pasture. Not all injuries are this bad - some people actually LIKE having certain warriors lose an arm, for instance - but it's definitely something you want to avoid.If you can deal with frustration well, like learning the ins and outs of a complicated system, and enjoy games that are both enraging and engaging, this might be the one for you.Also, I nominated this game for the made-up category of ""I'm Angry and I'm Loving It."" It seemed fitting."
