76561198005488263,Recommended,276810,23408427,"Posted: 5 June, 2016",all,Phill,"Having originally reviewed this game when it was released, I felt it necessary to alter my opinion of the game.In the beginning, this game is incredibly difficult to get going - the computer always has an advantage, you suffer losses whilst the computer cannot (because it matches your rating) and ultimately you are going to struggle out of the gate.But eventually the pendulum begins to shift in your favour - where you can optimise characters with the best weapons, armour and skills the computer tends to pick rather randomly (nothing says fun like a heavily armoured darksoul... with a dagger.)The game's movement system is exceptional in design and really helps you strategise, trying to eek out a way to charge for 5 minutes by manipulating the system. The RNG, while incredibly rough, does eventually tone itself down to the point where you can survive the bad luck with skill.Overall I feel with the improvements to the game and a bit of perseverence passed the initial setup the game is definitely worth playing for those who enjoy X-Com and other turn-based strategy games."
76561197968405486,Recommended,276810,25900270,"Posted: 7 October, 2016",all,ALWAYS. ALL THE TIME,"Ok my initial review panned this game.Now I have figured out that it is EXACTLY like the campaign mode of the skirmish games Mordheim and Necromunda, and should be played EXACTLY like those.Think XCOM 2 hardcore mode.  Take no risks.I freaking love it.Pros:It's pretty-ish. Not great, not awful.The involvement is as detailed as the tabletop rules for NecromundaA lot of thought has gone into the mechanics of combat.At no stage do you face a warband weaker than yours - Or Stronger.Enemy warbands ALWAYS match you - even wounds appear on themThe 'develop your warband' aspect is great, but you're always short of cash.Cons:You're always short of cash until you max level.  Sitting there with 5 Warband members who can't learn skills or spells because you don't have the cash is infuriation incarnate.You need to mob enemies to kill them...But you also need someone not in combat to go and scavenge so you can have enough gold to pay your warband.There are no difficulty levels.So if this is a game you just want to sit down and play through the story for, forget it.  Every mission is a struggle.There is no 'reload' mechanic, if your machine crashes, or the game bugs, you suffer massive hits to your entire warband, basically ending their career.The AI is 'Special' - gets opponents stuck on terrain a lot, targets your DLC heroes over all others, makes odd attack choices.Overall impression:The satisfaction of walking away from a fight with no casualties due to careful tactics is wonderful.Don't expect to have 'hero grunts'. Make your warriors fight as a team - they will last longer.READ ALL THE SKILLS.  This game lends itself to specific builds for warriors. e.g. tank, crit machine, fear monger etc.Specialists are more effective than generalists."
