76561198032773574,Recommended,276810,25003544,"Posted: 18 August, 2016",all,cj7822,"Okay, so this is actually my 3rd review of Mordheim.  After the first review I came to the conclusion that I may not have given the game it's fair amount of time invested, so I played and wrote the second review.  The second review was actually less favorable than the first due to all of the frustrations this title can bring.I love challenging games and Mordheim certainly does not disappoint.  Actually, to be honest, the difficulty level actually seemed to be too harsh.  There are some elements that don't quite seem fair or even at times, manageable.  I'll go into this a little to give you an idea to what you may be getting yourself into.  Basically you take your warband into battle against a rival warband with various side objectives but one common goal, to make your rival route (Retreat).  You achieve this by knocking your opponents units out of battle and once their morale is low enough they must pass a route test.  If they fail, they retreat.  If they pass, the battle ensues on that path. After battle, you have to pay to heal your injured units while also paying an upkeep cost for those units you took into battle.  If you lose the battle, you typically get no income.  Therefore, you have to pay costs but have little to no income to achieve this with if you fall in battle often.  And you will.  In addition to the side missions there will be the Campaign portion of the game.  One main mission that needs to be successfully completed before moving on to the next.  These missions have set ratings and this is the only time your warband can be stronger than that of the AI.  So, if you fail, strengthen your warband and try again.  Every other battle the AI will bring the same amount of units and the same type of units into battle that you do.  However, depending on the difficulty rating (Normal, Hard, Brutal, Deadly), their units will be a certain percentage stronger than yours.  Even on Normal, your units are slightly weaker than theirs, which adds to the difficulty but also the satisfaction when you win.This can all be very frustrating and even appear unfair at times, and it is.  It's all about the management of your warband and undergoing successful missions.  Now, don't be deceived by the amount of time I've put into this game.  I've played a ton offline and now that I have, I've obtained a better grasp on what works best in battle and certain techniques with the 4 starting warbands.  Another reason I initially opted not to recommend this game is because I didn't care for the clunky and unorganized UI.  Quite honestly, I still don't but the game had enough promise and kept me coming back for more punishment.  So much so that I purchased the PS4 version.  In that version I can say that the controls appear tighter and the UI is much more tolerable.With that being said, I've put a lot of time in on the PS4 version and now I can say this is my new favorite title that I own.  Both versions are identical, which is why I feel comfortable mentioning the PS4 vresion as I actually prefer it with the tight controls via the PS4 controller.Some pros of Mordheim are the amount of units per faction.  There are currently 7 different units you can recruit along with 2 additional units as dlc.  They are all of good variety in regards to their skills and attributes.  Also, each faction is vastly different from the others.Although the punishing difficulty can be a negative, it is also one of the strong points of the title.  When you win its much more satisfying and every move truly matters.  It really makes you think and play cautiously as everything is permanent.  And believe me, pernanent is PERMANENT.  There are no resets of any sort so be prepared to deal with the consequences.  The injuries your units can receive after being knocked out of battle are nothing short of awesome.  My leader recently had to have his leg amputated due to injury.  Now, he's running around with a peg leg, althought not quite as fast as he used to be lol.  Another lost an eye, another suffered a broken jaw...  You get the picture as each of these permanent injuries incur permanent penalties to their specific attributes.  All of this makes things all that more difficult but you learn to overcome some obstacles as you must to prevail!!!   Lol.One point I feel it necessary to touch on is that of the ""Veteran"" system.  You have this system in place, which grants additional perks to your warband in the form of lessening the cost to heal injured allies, or perks that grant discounts to purchase items from the shop.  There are a lot of perks to choose from.  The best part of this system is that it carries from one warband to another.  My current veteran rank is 6.  Which means I've received 6 points towards Perks, along with various upgrades such as additional gold for starting Warbands, additional slots to put more units into among several others.  In this system, when you start a new warband (Campaign), this new warband receives all of these additions, including the 6 points for perks I had unlocked.  These points start out inassigned so you can distribute them as you like, depending on your warband and it's needs with how you want to play.Final point I'll touch on is that of progression.  The system in place for progression is very good in my opinion.  There are 9 basic attributes divided into 3 categories.  After most battles, your units will receive points in one or more of these categorries and you decide which attribute to increase.  You also learn skills with each unit.  Some skills are active skills which you have to activate in battle and others are passive that are active all the time.  Some units can also cast spells so you do get spell points with these units as well as Skill points.  Each class of spellcaster has their own spells too, making strategy more important.  I've found it really pays off to properly mix your units, more so than in most other games because a lot of the skills/spells are for specific uses and strategies.In short, I now absolutely recommend this game.  As difficult and as punishing as it is, this is a title you have to spend time with, tweak your battleplan and find what works for you and your warband.  For a TBS game of this nature, its rare for me to find one that gives you that ""Just one more turn"" itch but this one does it...  Just one more match...  Then my guys start losing body parts...  I'll have to learn to quit while I'm ahead, but I know I won't.  Lol."
76561198010423636,Recommended,276810,20048701,"Posted: 28 December, 2015",all,blizzard5314,"It's not often someone walks away from a game in seething frustration to revisit it months later and fall in love with it for some of the same reasons they walked away from it in the first place. I think this game gave me Stockholm Syndrome.Mordheim is a simple but punishing tactical strategy game in which you control a small band of rats, a small band of lunatics, a small band of sexist male humans, or a small band of sexist female humans (The 4 base factions) and pit them against other small bands of random types in a winner-take-all quest to gather as many glowing green rocks as you can, or else your sponsoring organization (Doritos?) defaults on your Sally Mae college loan and then it's game over for you.But before you can enter the city with all those high hopes ready to be dashed to bits, you get to design your own band! The character models all look great, and there are small amounts of custom textures you can apply to give all your goons a personal touch. You also have the option to give them backstories, probably so it's all the more sorrowful when they see their ultimate end. The leader of my mercenary band, Herbert Halfscrotum, is still alive and kicking.Mordheim promises permanent deaths and injuries for your band, and has a million ways to ruin your expedition. Spells can fail, prayers can backfire, attacks can go horribly wrong, traps are everywhere, random neutral demons can hound your entire band into an early grave... even the rocks you are there to gather can drown you in negative effects. This is a great game for pessimists, because everything will go wrong and it pays to have contingencies.Gameplay is rough and slightly unbalanced in your enemy's favor. I don't think the RNG is rigged, but the AI warbands DO get a health and damage boost over yours, even on the lowest difficulties. I think this is to compensate for their blatant stupidity. Regardless, they aren't pushovers, and I've found the best tactic around is to let them split up like fools, let them charge you one at a time, and gangbust them Clockwork Orange-style. It may sound dirty, but more often than not, missions can feel like an uphill battle with the AI having an overt handicap as well as almost always having a higher power rating than you. I'd give that last comment a definite, but I actually ran into a band with 1 less point than me... but it was in a not-for-keeps exhibition. Go figure.There is a good game behind all this polarization, even if some people can't find the fun in something they can't consistently steamroll. If you were like me and fled in frustration over a lack of noob-friendliness, constantly cursing the RNG for why your heavily-armored tin can couldn't make that climb check and sustained permanent brain damage, consider swallowing your pride and giving it another go. You already bought it, after all. Just grab a few beers (or kale smoothies, or whatever), make a band you really believe in (All hail Herbert Halfscrotum!), and wade back into it. If you haven't purchased it yet, consider giving it a shot... even if you wait for a sale."
